# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-diaspora
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:african-diaspora/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] The **2022 Brazilian Census** was the 13th national population census in Brazilian history, and took place on 1 August 2022.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] It was intended to take place in 2020, but postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic and budgetary issues.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] Originally, the census, being carried out decennially, was supposed to take place in mid-2020.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] However, due to the current COVID-19 pandemic, the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics changed the date to 2021.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] However, in early 2021, the budget of census was cut from around 2 billion reais to 240 million, roughly 12% of the original budget.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] The census was pushed again, with Brazil's Supreme Court ruling that the government had to perform the census in 2022.
[src:african-diaspora/2022-brazilian-census] While the original reference date was 1 June 2022, the IBGE changed the date to 1 August 2022, due to the change in the company that would hire the workers.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Born in Franca, São Paulo state, Nascimento attended public school as a child and joined the military in 1929.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] In the 1930s Nascimento was a member of the Brazilian Integralist Action, a fascist party.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] He received a B.A. in Economics from the University of Rio de Janeiro in 1938, and graduate degrees from the Higher Institute of Brazilian Studies (1957) and the Oceanography Institute (1961).
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Then and there, he decided to create a black theater in Brazil to fight against racism.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] In Argentina, Nascimento spent a year with the "Teatro del Pueblo" (People's Theater) in Buenos Aires, where he learned the technical and performance aspects of theater.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Returning to São Paulo, he was imprisoned, having been convicted *in absentia* by the civilian court for the same incident of resisting racial discrimination for which he had been excluded from the Army.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] While in prison at the Carandiru Penitentiary, he created the Convict's Theater, in which prisoners wrote, directed, and performed in their own plays and musical productions.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] When released, Nascimento moved to Rio de Janeiro, where he founded the Black Experimental Theater (*Teatro Experimental do Negro*, TEN) in 1944.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] TEN premiered on May 8, 1945, with a production of O'Neill's *The Emperor Jones*, surprising skeptical critics with a presentation that was highly acclaimed for its technical and dramatic effectiveness.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] With intense activity in theatrical production, TEN also was responsible for stellar initiatives in black activism, such as the National Convention of Brazilian Blacks (1945–46), the Conference of Brazilian Blacks (1949), and the First Congress of Brazilian Blacks (1950).
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] A resolution of the 1950 congress advocated the need for a Black Arts Museum in Brazil, and the Black Experimental Theater embraced the project.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Many artists donated works and the first exhibition was held in 1968 at Rio de Janeiro's *Museu da Imagem e do Som* (Museum of Image and Sound).
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] The Black Experimental Theater organized the cast for the play *Orfeu da Conceição*, by Vinicius de Moraes, which was later adapted into the motion picture *Black Orpheus,* directed by Marcel Camus.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Nascimento became a leader in Brazil's black movement, and was forced into exile by the military regime in 1968.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] From 1968 to 1981 Nascimento was very active in the international Pan-African Movement and was elected vice-president and Coordinator of the Third Congress of Black Culture in the Americas.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] He held the position of Professor Emeritus at SUNY-Buffalo.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Nascimento also taught at the University of Ife (now Obafemi Awolowo University) in Nigeria.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Nascimento began painting after going into exile as a continuation of his activism through art, blending cultural expression with political resistance and the through restoration of the values of African culture.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Nascimento returned to Brazil in 1983 and was elected to the federal Chamber of Deputies as a member of the Democratic Labor Party (PDT).
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] There, his focus was supporting legislation to address racial problems.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] In 1994 he was elected to the Senate and served until 1999.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] In 2004 he was nominated for the Nobel Prize for Peace.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] He received honorary doctorates from the universities of Brasília and Rio de Janeiro, and the Universidade Federal da Bahia.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] A biography of Nascimento by the journalist Sandra Almada was published in 2009 as part of the *Retratos do Brasil Negro* series.
[src:african-diaspora/abdias-do-nascimento] Nascimento suffered from diabetes and died on 23 May 2011, in Rio de Janeiro, due to cardiac arrest.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] As leader of Niger, he oversaw a diplomatic standoff with ECOWAS stemming from the coup, the establishment of the Alliance of Sahel States, and withdrawal from ECOWAS.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He hails from Toukounous in the Tillabéri Region, a main recruitment area for the Nigerien army in the west of the country.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He completed his secondary education in the capital Niamey, graduating with a Baccalauréat in 1984.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He then joined the army and studied at the National School of Active Officers in Thiès, Senegal in the same year.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Before becoming Commander of the Presidential guard, he led forces in Zinder, Agadez, and Diffa regions where he combated drug trafficking.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In 1989, he was the first officer to make it to the site of the UTA Flight 772 crash in the Ténéré desert, for which he was decorated.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He also served in UN peacekeeping missions in the Ivory Coast, Sudan, and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He also served in the Multinational Joint Task Force set up by Niger, Chad, Nigeria and Cameroon to fight Boko Haram.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In 2011, Tchiani assumed command of the Presidential Guard and was a close ally of then-President Mahamadou Issoufou, who promoted him to general in 2018.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In 2015, Tchiani was accused of involvement in a coup plot against Issoufou but denied the charges in court.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He was otherwise regarded as keeping his views to himself during that time.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In 2021, Tchiani led the unit that thwarted an attempted coup; at the time a military unit tried to seize the presidential palace two days before Issoufou stepped down to make way for his democratically elected successor, Mohamed Bazoum, who retained Tchiani in his post.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] On 26 July 2023, Tchiani ordered presidential guards to detain Bazoum at his presidential residence in Niamey.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Bazoum was planning to relieve Tchiani from his position.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Sources close to Bazoum said that he had decided on Tchiani's dismissal at a cabinet meeting on 24 July as their relations had reportedly become strained.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] On 28 July, Tchiani revealed himself as the president of the National Council for the Safeguard of the Homeland, which took power on 26 July, in an address on state television.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He said the coup was undertaken to avoid "the gradual and inevitable demise" of the country and said that Bazoum had tried to hide "the harsh reality" of the country, which he called "a pile of dead, displaced, humiliation and frustration".
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] He also criticized the government's security strategy for its purported ineffectiveness.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] ECOWAS responded to the coup by imposing the strictest travel and economic sanctions the bloc ever imposed on a member state, demanding the reinstatement of Bazoum.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] As blackouts and supply disruptions roiled Niger, Tchiani criticized the sanctions as illegal and inhumane.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In a meeting with an ECOWAS delegation, Tchiani proposed a three-year window for a transition to civilian rule, which ECOWAS rejected in favor of an immediate transfer of power.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] ECOWAS lifted the sanctions for humanitarian reasons after Niger had departed the organization.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Under Tchiani's leadership, Niger established the Alliance of Sahel States with Burkina Faso and Mali in 2023, and left ECOWAS with them in 2024.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] US and EU troops were withdrawn from the country.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] The country also aligned itself closer to Russia and mercenary troops from the Wagner Group were sent to help Niger combat the Jihadist insurgents.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Analysts identified three main objectives of Tchiani's internal policy: modernizing the army, promoting economic growth (including a lessened dependence on uranium through investments in agriculture, infrastructure and renewable energy), and implementing an anti-corruption agenda.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In December 2024, Tchiani accused France and Nigeria of colluding with rebel groups to destabilize the Nigerien government, as well as accusing Nigeria of sabotaging the oil pipeline to Benin.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In January 2025, according to the World Health Organization, Niger became the first African country and the fifth country worldwide to eradicate onchocerciasis (a goal it had already been working towards for several years prior to the coup).
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Tchiani was formally sworn in as president on 26 March 2025, for a five year term, and promoted to the rank of general.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Like before the coup d'état, the economic system is based upon planning but accords an important role to private enterprise.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] The three main policy objectives are the maintenance of national unity, the elevation of the living standards of the population, and the attainment of economic independence.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] The private sector of the economy consists partly of a multitude of small enterprises and partly of enterprises belonging to large French or international companies.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In October 2023, sanctions and the suspension of international aid from ECOWAS left Niger as one of the poorest countries in the world.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] By October 2023, Niger's Nigelec state-owned utility company could only meet between a quarter and half of demand across the country.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In February 2024, a new regulatory law was enacted to secure unrestricted access to state resources.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Military spending is no longer subject to public procurement regulations.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] This has paved the way for faster processing of arms purchases, the use of mercenaries, and the alleged personal enrichment of the new rulers.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] In June 2024, the military junta revoked the operating licence of French nuclear fuel producer Orano at one of the world's biggest uranium mines.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Days later, it announced that the Imouraren mine had returned "to the state's public domain".
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] His prime minister and finance minister, Ali Lamine Zeine was affiliated with the MNSD-Nassara, a party which advocates for liberal economic policies.
[src:african-diaspora/abdourahamane-tchiani] Tchiani is married and has five children.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The region had autonomy as the Abkhaz Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic within the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic at the time when the Soviet Union began to disintegrate in the late 1980s.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The political status of Abkhazia is the central issue of the Abkhazia conflict and Georgia–Russia relations.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is formally recognised as an independent state by five UN member states (Russia, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Nauru, and Syria), with two other states having previously recognised but withdrawn their recognition (Tuvalu and Vanuatu).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The remainder of the international community recognises Abkhazia as *de jure* part of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Lacking effective control over the Abkhazian territory, Georgia maintains an Abkhaz government-in-exile.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Despite a 1994 ceasefire agreement and years of negotiations, the dispute remains unresolved.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The long-term presence of a United Nations Observer Mission and a Russian-led Commonwealth of Independent States peacekeeping force failed to prevent the flare-up of violence on several occasions.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In August 2008, Abkhaz and Russian forces fought the Russo-Georgian War against Georgian forces, which led to the formal recognition of Abkhazia by Russia, the annulment of the 1994 ceasefire agreement and the termination of the UN mission.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 23 October 2008, the Parliament of Georgia declared Abkhazia a Russian-occupied territory.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Russian name Абхазия (**Abkhaziya**) is adapted from the Georgian აფხაზეთი (**Apkhazeti**).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz name *Apsny* (Abkhaz: Аԥсны, IPA [apʰsˈnɨ]) is etymologised as 'a land of the soul'; however, the literal meaning is 'a country of mortals'.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] It possibly first appeared in the seventh century in an Armenian text, perhaps referring to the ancient Apsilians.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In early Muslim sources, the term *Abkhazia* was generally used to mean the territory of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Presumably considered as a successor of the Kingdom of *Laziǩa* (*Egrisi* in Georgian sources), this new polity continued to be referred to as *Egrisi* in some Byzantine era Georgian and Armenian chronicles (e.g.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] *The Vitae of the Georgian Kings* by Leonti Mroveli and *History of Armenia* by Hovhannes Draskhanakerttsi).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Constitution of Abkhazia says the names of the "Republic of Abkhazia" and "Apsny" are equivalent and interchangeable.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Before the 20th century, the region was sometimes referred to in English language sources as *Abhasia*.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Between the 9th and 6th centuries BC, the territory of modern Abkhazia was part of the ancient Kingdom of Colchis.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Around the 6th century BC, the Greeks established trade colonies along the Black Sea coast of present-day Abkhazia, in particular at Pitiunt and Dioscurias.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Classical authors described various peoples living in the region and the great multitude of languages they spoke.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Arrian, Pliny and Strabo have given accounts of the Abasgoi and Moschoi peoples somewhere in modern Abkhazia on the eastern shore of the Black Sea.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] This region was subsequently absorbed in 63 BC into the Kingdom of *Laziǩa*.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] According to an Eastern tradition, Simon the Zealot died in Abkhazia during a missionary trip and was buried in Nicopsis; his mortal remains were later transferred to Anacopia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Roman Empire conquered Lazica in the 1st century AD; however, the Roman presence was confined to port cities.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] According to Arrian, the Abasgoi and Apsilae peoples were nominal Roman subjects, and there was a small Roman outpost in Dioscurias.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abasgoi likely served in the Roman army in *Ala Prima Abasgorum*, which was stationed in Egypt.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] After the 4th century Lazica regained a measure of independence, but remained within the Byzantine Empire's sphere of influence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Anacopia was the principality's capital.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The country was mostly Christian, with the archbishop's seat in Pityus.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Stratophilus, the Metropolitan of Pityus, participated in the First Council of Nicaea in 325.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Around the middle of the 6th century AD, the Byzantines and the neighbouring Sassanid Persia fought for supremacy over Abkhazia, a conflict known as the Lazic War.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] During the war the Abasgians revolted against the Byzantine Empire and requested Sasanian assistance; the revolt was suppressed by General Bessas.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] An Arab incursion into Abasgia, led by Marwan II, was repelled by Prince Leon I jointly with his Lazic and Iberian allies in 736.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Leon I then married Mirian's daughter and a successor, King Leon II exploited this dynastic union to acquire Lazica in the 770s.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The successful defence against the Arab Caliphate, and new territorial gains in the east gave the Abasgian princes enough power to claim more autonomy from the Byzantine Empire.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Circa 778, Prince Leon II, with the help of the Khazars, declared independence from the Byzantine Empire and transferred his residence to Kutaisi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] During this period the Georgian language replaced Greek as the language of literacy and culture.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Kingdom of Abkhazia flourished between 850 and 950 AD, which ended by unification of Abkhazia and eastern Georgian states under a single Georgian monarchy ruled by King Bagrat III at the end of the 10th century and the beginning of the 11th century.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] During the reign of Queen Tamar, Georgian chronicles mention Otagho as the Eristavi of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] He was one of the first representatives of the House of Shervashidze (also known as Chachba) which went on to rule Abkhazia until the 19th century.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the 1240s, Mongols divided Georgia into eight military-administrative sectors (tümens).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The territory of contemporary Abkhazia formed part of the tümen administered by Tsotne Dadiani.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the 16th century, after the break-up of the Georgian Kingdom into small kingdoms and principalities, the Principality of Abkhazia (nominally a vassal of the Kingdom of Imereti) emerged, ruled by the Shervashidze dynasty.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In 1453, the Ottomans first attacked Sukhumi, and in the 1570s, they had a garrison there.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Throughout the 17th century, they continued to launch attacks, leading to the imposition of tribute on Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Ottoman influence grew significantly in the 18th century with the construction of a fort in Sukhumi, accompanied by a conversion of the rulers of Abkhazia and many other Abkhaz to Islam.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Nonetheless, conflicts between the Abkhaz and Turks persisted.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The spread of Islam in Abkhazia was first evidenced by the Ottoman traveller Evliya Çelebi in 1641.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Despite this, the Islamisation was more evident in the higher levels of society rather than the general population.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In his work, Çelebi also wrote that the principal tribe of the Abkhazian principality, Chách, spoke the Mingrelian language, a subset of Kartvelian (Georgian) languages.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia sought protection from the Russian Empire in 1801 but was declared "an autonomous principality" by the Russians in 1810.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Russia then annexed Abkhazia in 1864, and Abkhaz resistance was quashed as the Russians deported Muslim Abkhaz to Ottoman territories.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the beginning of the 19th century, while the Russians and Ottomans were vying for control of the region, the rulers of Abkhazia shifted back and forth across the religious divide.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The first attempt to enter into relations with Russia was made by Prince Kelesh-Bey in 1803, shortly after the incorporation of eastern Georgia into the expanding Tsarist empire in 1801.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] However, pro-Ottoman sympathy in Abkhazia prevailed for a short time after Kelesh-Bey was assassinated by his son, Aslan-Bey, in 1801.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 2 July 1810, Russian Marines stormed Sukhum-Kale and had Aslan-Bey replaced with his rival and brother, Sefer Ali-Bey, who had converted to Christianity and assumed the name of George.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia joined the Russian Empire as an autonomous principality, in 1810.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] However, Sefer-bey's rule was limited and many mountain regions were as independent as before.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The next Russo-Turkish war (1828–1829) strongly enhanced the Russian positions, leading to a further split in the Abkhaz elite, mainly along religious divisions.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] During the Crimean War (1853–1856), Russian forces had to evacuate Abkhazia and Prince Hamud-Bey Sharvashidze-Chachba (Mikhail), who ruled from 1822 to 1864, seemingly switched to the Ottomans.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Later on, the Russian presence strengthened and the highlanders of Western Caucasia were finally subjugated by Russia in 1864.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Later that same year, Abkhazia was incorporated into the Russian Empire as a special military province of Sukhum-Kale which was transformed, in 1883, into an *okrug* as part of the Kutaisi Governorate.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Large numbers of Muslim Abkhazians, said to have constituted as much as 40% of the Abkhazian population, emigrated to the Ottoman Empire between 1864 and 1878 together with other Muslim populations of the Caucasus, a process known as *Muhajirism*.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Large areas of the region were left uninhabited and many Armenians, Georgians, Russians and others subsequently migrated to Abkhazia, resettling much of the vacated territory.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Some Georgian historians assert that Georgian tribes (Svans and Mingrelians) had populated Abkhazia since the time of the Colchis kingdom.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Russian government had plans to colonize Abkhazia with Russian settlers, and created a special legal framework granting land allocations to Russians to encourage their migration.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] However, the Russian colonization efforts failed because of the lack of roads connecting Abkhazia to the main economic centers in Southern Russia, the unfamiliarity of the Russian settlers with local climate and agriculture, and their high susceptibility to malaria (leading to some deaths).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] This led to the other ethnic groups, which the Russian government did not plan to be settled in Abkhazia, to migrate spontaneously and outnumber the Russians in the region.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] This included former Ottoman subjects, such as Greeks and Armenians, and Mingrelians from the neighboring province within the empire.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Both were more familiar with the local climate and were less susceptible to malaria.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Mingrelians became the largest group of arrivals, despite being marginalized as an agricultural labor force due to the lack of state support and legal restrains placed on them.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Their arrival alarmed the Russian authorities, because they saw the Mingrelian migration as an impediment to the Russian colonization, and the Russian government responded with the legal measures to restrict the settlement of Mingrelians in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The same policy was conducted to alienate Abkhazians from Georgians despite their common historical heritage and few problems historically.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the case of the Abkhaz, Russia attempted to obviate the use of the Georgian language by Abkhazians which they previously wielded as the second language and used for the literacy and high culture.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Instead, the Russian authorities put an effort to substitute Georgian with the Russian language.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] A separate Abkhaz alphabet was created based on Cyrillic script and the teaching of the Russian language to Abkhazians was mandated.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] By official decision of the Russian authorities, the residents of Abkhazia and Samurzakano had to study and pray in Russian.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] After the mass deportation of 1878, Abkhazians were left in the minority, officially branded "guilty people", and had no leader capable of mounting serious opposition to Russification.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 17 March 1898, the synodal department of the Russian Orthodox Church of Georgia-Imereti, by Order 2771, again prohibited teaching and the conduct of religious services in Georgian.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Mass protests by the Georgian population of Abkhazia and Samurzakano followed, news of which reached the Russian emperor.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 3 September 1898 the Holy Synod issued Order 4880, which decreed that those parishes where the congregation was Mingrelian (i.e.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Georgian), conduct both church services and church education in Georgian, while Abkhazian parishes use old Slavic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the Sukhumi district, this order was carried out in only three of 42 parishes.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Tedo Sakhokia demanded the Russian authorities introduce Abkhazian and Georgian languages in church services and education.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The official response was a criminal case brought against Tedo Sakhokia and leaders of his "Georgian Party" active in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In 1904, the territory of Gagra District was detached from Sukhumi okrug and joined to the Black Sea Governorate after Duke Alexander of Oldenburg, a member of the Russian royalty, built a resort there.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] By the early 20th century, the Georgians, represented by Samurzakanians and Mingrelians, were the largest group in Abkhazia, but from the social point of view, they were the most disadvantaged and marginalized group, being agricultural workers with severe restrictions on their residential status.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz and the Russians were the well-off groups which controlled large amounts of land and were well-represented in the nobility and bureaucracy.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Armenians and Greeks were mostly involved in the tobacco industry.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Following the October Revolution in Russia, the Transcaucasian Commissariat was set up in Southern Caucasus, which gradually took steps towards the independence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Transcaucasia declared its independence from Russia on 9 April 1918 as a federative republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 8 May 1918, the Bolsheviks seized power in Abkhazia and disbanded the local Abkhaz People's Council.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] It requested aid from the Transcausian authorities, which dispatched the Georgian People's Guard and defeated the rebels on 17 May.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 26 May 1918, Georgia declared independence from the Transcaucasian Federation, which dissolved on 28 May.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 8 June 1918, the Abkhaz People's Council signed a treaty with the Georgian National Council, which confirmed Abkhazia's status as an autonomy within the Georgian Democratic Republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian army defeated another Bolshevik rebellion in the region.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] It remained part of Georgia after another Bolshevik revolt and a Turkish expedition were defeated in 1918.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Russian general and a leader of White movement Anton Denikin laid claims on Abkhazia and captured Gagra, but the Georgians counter-attacked in April 1919 and retook the city.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Denikin's Volunteer Army was eventually defeated by the Red Army, and Bolshevik Russia signed an agreement with Georgia in May 1920, recognising Abkhazia as a part of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In 1919, a first election was held to the Abkhaz People's Council.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Council favoured being an autonomous region within Georgia, and it lasted until the Red Army invasion of Georgia in February 1921.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 20 March 1919, the newly elected Abkhazian People's Council adopted the "Act on Abkhazian Autonomy", which formalised the establishment of the Abkhazian Autonomy within the Georgian Democratic Republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In 1921, the Bolshevik Red Army invaded Georgia and ended its short-lived independence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia was made a Socialist Soviet Republic (SSR Abkhazia) with the ambiguous status of a "*treaty republic"* associated with the Georgian SSR.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Under the *korenizatsiia* policy of the Soviet Union, the Abkhaz people were not considered the "advanced" people, and thus saw an increased focus on their national language and cultural development.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Under this nationalities policy, the Abkhaz received various benefits such as schooling in their language; the official literary language was established for the first time.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Between 1922 and 1926, the share of Abkhazes increased from 19.8% to 27.8% of the population (possibly due to the immigration of ethnic Abkhaz from Turkey or re-identification as Abkhaz).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Their share among the members of the local communist party grew from 10% to the 25%.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Meanwhile, the proportion of the ethnic Georgian population decreased from 42% in 1922 to 36% in 1926, while their proportion in the local communist party also decreased from 40% to 33%.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The report noted that all major posts were held by the Abkhaz, they were overrepresented in the local structures such as the police, and the local Komsomol was only admitting ethnic Abkhazians.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In 1931, Joseph Stalin made Abkhazia an autonomous republic (Abkhaz ASSR) within the Georgian SSR.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the Terror of 1937–38, the ruling elite was purged of Abkhazes and by 1952 over 80% of the 228 top party and government officials and enterprise managers were ethnic Georgians; there remained 34 Abkhazes, 7 Russians, and 3 Armenians in these positions.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Georgian Communist Party leader Kandid Charkviani supported the Georgianization of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Starting from 1939, peasant households from the rest of the Georgian SSR were resettled to Abkhazia which changed its demographic makeup significantly.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Georgians were the largest ethnic group in Abkhazia even before Stalin's policies.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The publishing of materials in Abkhazian dwindled and was eventually stopped altogether; Abkhaz schools were closed in 1945–1946, requiring Abkhaz children to study in the Georgian language.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The teaching of the Abkhaz language was preserved in the new reorganised Abkhaz schools as a mandatory subject by the decision of the Georgian Communist Party.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The policy of repression was eased after Stalin's death and Beria's execution, and the Abkhaz were given a greater role in the governance of the republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] As in most of the smaller autonomous republics, the Soviet government encouraged the development of culture and particularly of literature.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhazian ASSR was the only autonomous republic in the USSR in which the language of the titular nation (in that case Abkhaz) was confirmed in its constitution as one of its official languages.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the post-war period, the Abkhazian ASSR was dominated by the ethnic Abkhazes, who occupied many more positions in the autonomous republic compared to Georgians.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] During the late Soviet period, ethnic Abkhazes occupied 41% of the seats in Abkhazian Supreme Soviet, and 67% of the republican ministers were ethnically Abkhaz.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Moreover, they held even larger proportion of lower level official posts within the autonomous republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The first secretary of the communist party in Abkhazia was also ethnically Abkhaz.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] All of this was despite the fact that Abkhazians made up only 17.8% of the region's population, while Georgians made up 45.7%, and other ethnicities (Greeks, Russians, Armenians, etc.) made up 36.5%.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] As the Soviet Union began to disintegrate at the end of the 1980s, ethnic tensions grew between the Abkhaz and Georgians over Georgia's moves towards independence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Many Abkhaz opposed this, fearing that an independent Georgia would lead to the elimination of their autonomy, and argued instead for the establishment of Abkhazia as a separate Soviet republic in its own right.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] With the onset of perestroika, the agenda of Abkhaz nationalists became more radical and exclusive.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In 1988, they began to ask for the reinstatement of Abkhazia's former status of Union Republic, as the submission of Abkhazia to another Union Republic was not considered to give enough guarantees of their development.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] They justified their request by referring to the Leninist tradition of the right of nations to self-determination, which they asserted was violated when Abkhazia's sovereignty was curtailed in 1931.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In June 1988, a manifesto defending Abkhaz distinctiveness (known as the Abkhazian Letter) was sent to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian–Abkhaz dispute turned violent on 16 July 1989 in Sukhumi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Numerous Georgians were killed or injured when they tried to enroll in a Georgian university instead of an Abkhaz one.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] After several days of violence, Soviet troops restored order in the city.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In March 1990, Georgia declared sovereignty, unilaterally nullifying treaties concluded by the Soviet government since 1921 and thereby moving closer to independence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Most ethnic non-Georgians in Abkhazia later boycotted a 31 March referendum on Georgia's independence, which was supported by a huge majority of Georgian population.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Within weeks, Georgia declared independence on 9 April 1991, under former Soviet dissident Zviad Gamsakhurdia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Under Gamsakhurdia, the situation was relatively calm in Abkhazia and a power-sharing agreement was soon reached between the Abkhaz and Georgian factions, granting to the Abkhaz a certain over-representation in the local legislature.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Under the compromise solution negotiated in August 1991, the Abkhaz received an ethnic quota of 28 seats in the Abkhazian Supreme Soviet, despite being only 18% of the population.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Georgians, making up 46% of the population, got 26 seats, while the rest received 11 seats.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] A two-thirds majority was to be required to pass constitutional changes to ensure that key decisions would not be taken without approval from both Abkhaz and Georgian deputies and each side would hold veto power in principle.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The elections using this scheme were held in late 1991.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Gamsakhurdia's rule was soon challenged by armed opposition groups, under the command of Tengiz Kitovani, that forced him to flee the country in a military coup in January 1992.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Gamsakhurdia was replaced by former Soviet Georgian leader and Soviet foreign minister Eduard Shevardnadze, who became the country's head of state.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 21 February 1992, Georgia's ruling military council announced that it was abolishing the Soviet-era constitution and restoring the 1921 Constitution of the Democratic Republic of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Many Abkhaz interpreted this as an abolition of their autonomous status, although the 1921 constitution contained a provision for the region's autonomy.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 23 July 1992, the Abkhaz faction in the republic's Supreme Soviet declared effective independence from Georgia, although the session was boycotted by ethnic Georgian deputies and the gesture went unrecognised by any other country.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz leadership launched a campaign of ousting Georgian officials from their offices, a process which was accompanied by violence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the meantime, the Abkhaz leader Vladislav Ardzinba intensified his ties with hardline Russian politicians and military elite and declared he was ready for a war with Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] To respond to this situation, Eduard Shevardnadze, new leader of Georgia, interrupted his trip to Western Georgia, where he was touring cities still supporting ousted Gamsakhurdia and was being met by heckling.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze announced that the decision of the Abkhaz faction was "absolutely unexpected" and that it was made without considering the opinion of the majority of population in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In August 1992, the National Guard of Georgia, led by Tengiz Kitovani entered in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The declared goal was to free Georgian officials held captive in Abkhazia, and to reopen the railway line running through Abkhazia to the rest of Georgia, which was frequently robbed.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] According to Darrell Slider, Abkhaz troops were the first to open fire.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] This led to the beginning of the War in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz separatist government retreated to Gudauta where the Russian military base was located.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees reported the ethnic-based violence against Georgians in Gudauta.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz were relatively unarmed at the time and the Georgian troops were able to march into the capital Sukhumi with relatively little resistance and subsequently engaged in ethnically based pillage, looting, assault, and murder.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] They sided with the Abkhaz separatists to fight against the Georgian government.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Russian military did not impede the crossing of the Russia-Georgia border by the North Caucasian militants into Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the case of Basayev, it has been suggested that when he and the members of his battalion came to Abkhazia, they received training by the Russian Army (though others dispute this), presenting another possible motive.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On September 25, 1992, Russian Supreme Council (parliament) passed a resolution which condemned Georgia, supported Abkhazia and called for the suspension of the delivery of any weapons and equipment to Georgia and the deployment of a Russian peacekeeping force in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] It was sponsored by a Russian nationalist politician Sergei Baburin, a Russian deputy who met Vladislav Ardzinba and argued that he was not that much sure that Abkhazia was part of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In October, the Abkhaz and North Caucasian paramilitaries mounted a major offensive against Gagra after breaking a cease-fire, which drove the Georgian forces out of large swathes of the republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze's government accused Russia of giving covert military support to the rebels with the aim of "detaching from Georgia its native territory and the Georgia-Russian frontier land".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] 1992 ended with the rebels in control of much of Abkhazia northwest of Sukhumi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The conflict was in stalemate until July 1993, when Abkhaz separatist militias launched an abortive attack on Georgian-held Sukhumi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] They surrounded and heavily shelled the capital, where Shevardnadze was trapped.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The warring sides agreed to a Russian-brokered truce in Sochi at the end of July.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] But the ceasefire broke down again on 16 September 1993.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz forces, with armed support from outside Abkhazia, launched attacks on Sukhumi and Ochamchire.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Notwithstanding UN Security Council's call for the immediate cessation of hostilities and its condemnation of the violation of the ceasefire by the Abkhaz side, fighting continued.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] After ten days of heavy fighting, Sukhumi was taken by Abkhazian forces on 27 September 1993.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze narrowly escaped death, after vowing to stay in the city no matter what.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] He changed his mind, however, and decided to flee when separatist snipers fired on the hotel where he was staying.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz, North Caucasian militants, and their allies committed numerous atrocities against the city's remaining ethnic Georgians, in what has been dubbed the Sukhumi Massacre.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The mass killings and destruction continued for two weeks, leaving thousands dead and missing.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz forces quickly overran the rest of Abkhazia as the Georgian government faced a second threat; an uprising by the supporters of the deposed Zviad Gamsakhurdia in the region of Mingrelia (Samegrelo).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Only a small region of eastern Abkhazia, the upper Kodori gorge, remained under Georgian control (until 2008).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] During the war, gross human rights violations were reported on both sides.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Georgian troops have been accused of having committed looting and murders "for the purpose of terrorising, robbing and driving the Abkhaz population out of their homes" in the first phase of the war (according to Human Rights Watch).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Summits in Budapest (1994), Lisbon (1996) and Istanbul (1999) have recognized the ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia in 1992-1993 by the Abkhaz forces and their allies.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] While both sides have committed atrocities, the Abkhaz side has been singled out as responsible for a deliberate displacement campaign "carried out as a military, strategic and political objective in its".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Before the 1992 War in Abkhazia, Georgians made up nearly half of Abkhazia's population, while less than one-fifth of the population was Abkhaz.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] As the war progressed, confronted with hundreds of thousands of ethnic Georgians who were unwilling to leave their homes, the Abkhaz separatists implemented the process of ethnic cleansing in order to expel and eliminate the Georgian ethnic population in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] About 5,000 were killed, 400 went missing and up to 250,000 ethnic Georgians were expelled from their homes.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] According to International Crisis Group, as of 2006 slightly over 200,000 Georgians remained displaced in Georgia proper.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The campaign of ethnic cleansing also included Russians, Armenians, Greeks, moderate Abkhaz and other minor ethnic groups living in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] More than 20,000 houses owned by ethnic Georgians were destroyed.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Hundreds of schools, kindergartens, churches, hospitals, and historical monuments were pillaged and destroyed.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Following the process of ethnic cleansing and mass expulsion, the population of Abkhazia was reduced from 525,000 in 1989 to 216,000 in 2012.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Pogroms against ethnic Georgians organised by Abkhaz leaders continued even after the end of war, as late as February 1995.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Of about 250,000 Georgian refugees, some 60,000 subsequently returned to Abkhazia's Gali District between 1994 and 1998, but tens of thousands were displaced again when fighting resumed in the Gali District in 1998.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Nevertheless, between 40,000 and 60,000 refugees have returned to the Gali District since 1998, including persons commuting daily across the ceasefire line and those migrating seasonally in accordance with agricultural cycles.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The human rights situation remained precarious for a while in the Georgian-populated areas of the Gali District.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Key officials of the Gali District are virtually all ethnic Abkhaz, though their support staff are ethnic Georgian.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The ethnic Georgians in Gali are deprived of voting rights: during the 2021 local elections, only 900 eligible voters were registered in the Gali district, despite the 30,259 residents in the area.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Presidential elections were held in Abkhazia on 3 October 2004.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Russia supported Raul Khajimba, the prime minister backed by the ailing outgoing separatist President Vladislav Ardzinba.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Posters of Russia's President Vladimir Putin together with Khajimba, who, like Putin, had worked as a KGB official, were everywhere in Sukhumi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Deputies of Russia's parliament and Russian singers, led by Joseph Cobsohn, a State Duma deputy and a popular singer, came to Abkhazia, campaigning for Khajimba.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] However, Khajimba lost the elections to Sergei Bagapsh.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The tense situation in the republic led to the cancellation of the election results by the Supreme Court.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] After that, a deal was struck between former rivals to run jointly, with Bagapsh as a presidential candidate and Khajimba as a vice-presidential candidate.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] They received more than 90% of the votes in the new election.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In July 2006, Georgian forces launched a successful police operation against the rebelled administrator of the Georgian-populated Kodori Valley, Emzar Kvitsiani.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Kvitsiani had been appointed by the previous president of Georgia, Eduard Shevardnadze, and refused to recognise the authority of president Mikheil Saakashvili, who succeeded Shevardnadze after the Rose Revolution.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Although Kvitsiani escaped capture by Georgian police, the Kodori Gorge was brought back under the control of the central government in Tbilisi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Sporadic acts of violence continued throughout the postwar years.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Despite the peacekeeping status of the Russian peacekeepers in Abkhazia, Georgian officials routinely claimed that Russian peacekeepers were inciting violence by supplying Abkhaz rebels with arms and financial support.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Russian support of Abkhazia became pronounced when the Russian ruble became the de facto currency and Russia began issuing passports to the population of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Georgia has also accused Russia of violating its airspace by sending helicopters to attack Georgian-controlled towns in the Kodori Gorge.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In April 2008, a Russian MiG – prohibited from Georgian airspace, including Abkhazia – shot down a Georgian UAV.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 9 August 2008, Abkhazian forces fired on Georgian forces in Kodori Gorge.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] This coincided with the 2008 South Ossetia war where Russia decided to support the Ossetian separatists who had been attacked by Georgia after Russia provoked Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The conflict escalated into a full-scale war between the Russian Federation and the Republic of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 10 August 2008, an estimated 9,000 Russian soldiers entered Abkhazia ostensibly to reinforce the Russian peacekeepers in the republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] About 1,000 Abkhazian soldiers moved to expel the residual Georgian forces within Abkhazia in the Upper Kodori Gorge.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] By 12 August the Georgian forces and civilians had evacuated the last part of Abkhazia under Georgian government control.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Russia recognised the independence of Abkhazia on 26 August 2008.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] This was followed by the annulment of the 1994 ceasefire agreement and the termination of UN and OSCE monitoring missions.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 28 August 2008, the Parliament of Georgia passed a resolution declaring Abkhazia a Russian-occupied territory.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Since independence was recognised by Russia, a series of controversial agreements were made between the Abkhazian government and the Russian Federation that leased or sold a number of key state assets and relinquished control over the borders.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In May 2009 several opposition parties and war veteran groups protested against these deals complaining that they undermined state sovereignty and risked "exchanging one colonial power [Georgia] for another [Russia]".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The vice-president, Raul Khajimba, resigned on 28 May saying he agreed with the criticism the opposition had made.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Subsequently, a conference of opposition parties nominated Raul Khajimba as their candidate in the December 2009 Abkhazian presidential election won by Sergei Bagapsh.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In the spring of 2014, the opposition submitted an ultimatum to President Aleksandr Ankvab to dismiss the government and make radical reforms.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On 27 May 2014, in the centre of Sukhumi, 10,000 supporters of the Abkhaz opposition gathered for a mass demonstration.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] On the same day, Ankvab's headquarters in Sukhumi was stormed by opposition groups led by Raul Khajimba, forcing him into flight to Gudauta.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The opposition claimed that the protests were sparked by poverty, but the main point of contention was President Ankvab's liberal policy towards ethnic Georgians in the Gali region.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The opposition said these policies could endanger Abkhazia's ethnic Abkhazian identity.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] After Ankvab fled the capital, on 31 May, the People's Assembly of Abkhazia appointed parliamentary speaker Valery Bganba as acting president, declaring Ankvab unable to serve.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] It also decided to hold an early presidential election on 24 August 2014.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Ankvab soon declared his formal resignation, although he accused his opponents of acting immorally and violating the constitution.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Raul Khajimba was later elected president, taking office in September 2014.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In November 2014, Vladimir Putin moved to formalise the Abkhazian military's relationship as part of the Russian armed forces, signing a treaty with Khajimba.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian government denounced the agreement as "a step towards annexation".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Khajimba was re-elected with a margin of less than 2% in 2019.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] In January 2020 the Abkhazian Supreme Court annulled the results, following protests against Khajimba.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Khajimba resigned the presidency on 12 January, and new elections were called for 22 March.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Aslan Bzhania was elected in the subsequent elections with around 59% of the vote.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Protests took place in November 2024 after the arrest of five opposition activists who opposed an investment agreement with Russia, which led to the resignation of then–President Aslan Bzhania and a new presidential election in February 2025.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Acting president Badra Gunba was elected, receiving 56% of the vote.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia covers an area of about 8,665 km2 (3,346 sq mi) at the western end of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Caucasus Mountains to the north and northeast separate Abkhazia and the Russian Federation.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] To the east and southeast, Abkhazia is bounded by the Georgian region of Samegrelo-Zemo Svaneti; and on the south and southwest by the Black Sea.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is diverse geographically with lowlands stretching to the extremely mountainous north.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Greater Caucasus Mountain Range runs along the region's northern border, with its spurs – the Gagra, Bzyb and Kodori ranges – dividing the area into a number of deep, well-watered valleys.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The highest peaks of Abkhazia are in the northeast and east and several exceed 4,000 metres (13,123 ft) above sea level.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia's landscape ranges from coastal forests and citrus plantations to permanent snows and glaciers in the north of the region.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Although Abkhazia's complex topographic setting has spared most of the territory from significant human development, its cultivated fertile lands produce tea, tobacco, wine and fruits, a mainstay of the local agricultural sector.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is richly irrigated by small rivers originating in the Caucasus Mountains.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Chief of these are: Kodori, Bzyb, Ghalidzga, and Gumista.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The Psou River separates the region from Russia, and the Inguri serves as a boundary between Abkhazia and Georgia proper.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] There are several periglacial and crater lakes in mountainous Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Lake Ritsa is the most important of them.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Because of Abkhazia's proximity to the Black Sea and the shield of the Caucasus Mountains, the region's climate is very mild.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The coastal areas of the republic have a subtropical climate, where the average annual temperature in most regions is around 15 °C (59 °F), and the average January temperature remains above freezing.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The climate at higher elevations varies from maritime mountainous to cold and summerless.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Also, due to its position on the windward slopes of the Caucasus, Abkhazia receives high amounts of precipitation, though humidity decreases further inland.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The mountains of Abkhazia receive significant amounts of snow.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The world's deepest known cave, Veryovkina Cave, is located in Abkhazia's western Caucasus mountains.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The latest survey (as of March 2018) has measured the vertical extent of this cave system as 2,212 metres (7,257 ft) between its highest and lowest explored points.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The lowland regions used to be covered by swaths of oak, beech, and hornbeam, which have since been cleared.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] There are two main entrances into Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The southern entrance is at the Inguri bridge, a short distance from the city of Zugdidi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] The northern entrance ("Psou") is in the town of Leselidze.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] Owing to the situation with a recognition controversy, many foreign governments advise their citizens against travelling to Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p01] According to President Raul Khajimba, over the summer of 2015, thousands of tourists visited Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Legislative powers are vested in the People's Assembly, which consists of 35 elected members.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The last parliamentary elections were held in March 2022.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Ethnicities other than Abkhaz (Armenians, Russians and Georgians) are claimed to be under-represented in the Assembly.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Most refugees from the 1992–1993 war (mainly ethnic Georgians) have not been able to return and have thus been excluded from the political process.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Some refugees have been allowed to return, in particular in the Gali district where 98% of the population is Georgian as it was before the ethnic cleansing, however, they have been stripped of the voting and other rights.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As such, during the 2021 local elections, only 900 eligible voters were registered in the Gali district, despite the 30,259 residents in the area.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The territory of the Gali district has also been diminished through addition of some of its lands to Tkvarcheli and Ochamchire districts.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia has a major military and economic presence in Abkhazia, and the relationship between the two has been described as asymmetrical, with Abkhazia being heavily dependent on Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has adopted Russian technical and commercial standards, and large part of its infrastructure is owned by Russian companies, with Russia heavily investing in the military infrastructure.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The 2014 Treaty on Alliance and Strategic Partnership obliges Abkhazia to coordinate its foreign policy with Russia and merge the armed forces.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As such, under pressure from Russia, Abkhazia joined Russia in imposing sanctions on Turkey in 2016, becoming Russia's only ally to do so.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazian officials have stated that they have given the Russian Federation the responsibility of representing their interests abroad.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Some have described Abkhazia as Russia's protectorate with a strong and one-sided dependence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to a 2010 study published by the University of Colorado Boulder, the vast majority of Abkhazia's population supports independence, while a smaller number is in favour of joining the Russian Federation.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Support for reunification with Georgia is very low.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Among ethnic Abkhaz, explicit support for reunification with Georgia is around 1%; a similar figure can be found among ethnic Russians and Armenians as well.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] However, those supporting reunification with Georgia, including ethnic Abkhazians, have faced harassment by the separatist authorities in form of arrests and coercion to apologize publicly.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, separatist Republic of Abkhazia and Russian Federation signed the "Treaty of Alliance and Strategic Partnership" with Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Based on this treaty, in November 2020, Abkhazia launched a programme on the "formation of common social and economic space" with Russia to make Abkhaz laws and administrative measures more similar to Russian ones in social, economic, health and political spheres.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 15 August 2024, the Russian Deputy Minister of Economic Development Dmitry Volvach said that the process of Abkhazia's harmonisation of its laws with Russia was "almost complete".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Government of the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia is the government in exile that Georgia recognises as the legal government of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] This pro-Georgian government maintained a foothold on Abkhazian territory, in the upper Kodori Valley from July 2006 until it was forced out by fighting in August 2008.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] This government is also partly responsible for the affairs of some 250,000 IDPs, forced to leave Abkhazia following the War in Abkhazia and ethnic cleansing that followed.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The current Head of the Government is Giorgi Jincharadze.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] During this period, the Government of Abkhazia in exile, led by Tamaz Nadareishvili, was known for a hard-line stance towards the Abkhaz problem and frequently voiced their opinion that the solution to the conflict can be attained only through Georgia's military response to secessionism.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Later, Nadareishvili's administration was implicated in some internal controversies and had not taken an active part in the politics of Abkhazia until a new chairman, Irakli Alasania, was appointed by President of Georgia, Mikheil Saakashvili, his envoy in the peace talks over Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Republic of Abkhazia is divided into seven raions (districts) named after their primary cities: Gagra, Gudauta, Sukhumi, Ochamchira, Gulripshi, Tkvarcheli and Gali.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] These districts remain mostly unchanged since the break-up of the Soviet Union, with the exception of the Tkvarcheli District, created in 1995 from parts of the Ochamchira and Gali districts.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The President of the Republic appoints districts' heads from those elected to the districts' assemblies.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] There are elected village assemblies whose heads are appointed by the districts' heads.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The administrative subdivisions under Georgian law are identical to the ones outlined above, except for the new Tkvarcheli district.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhazian Armed Forces are the military of the Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The basis of the Abkhazian armed forces was formed by the ethnically Abkhaz National Guard, which was established in early 1992.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Most of their weapons come from the former Russian airborne division base in Gudauta.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhazian military is primarily a ground force, but includes small sea and air units.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia deploys its own military units as part of the 7th Military Base in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] These units are reportedly subordinate to the Russian 49th Army and include both ground elements and air defence assets.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia, Transnistria, and South Ossetia are post-Soviet "frozen conflict" zones.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] These three states maintain friendly relations with each other and form the Community for Democracy and Rights of Nations.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia and Nicaragua officially recognised Abkhazia after the Russo-Georgian War.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Venezuela recognised Abkhazia in September 2009.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In December 2009, Nauru recognised Abkhazia, reportedly in return for $50 million in humanitarian aid from Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The unrecognised republic of Transnistria and the partially recognised republic of South Ossetia have recognised Abkhazia since 2006.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia is also a member of the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization (UNPO).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] A majority of sovereign states recognise Abkhazia as an integral part of Georgia and support its territorial integrity according to the principles of international law, although Belarus has expressed sympathy toward the recognition of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Some have officially noted Abkhazia as under occupation by the Russian military.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The United Nations has been urging both sides to settle the dispute through diplomatic dialogue and ratifying the final status of Abkhazia in the Georgian constitution.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] However, the Abkhaz *de facto* government considers Abkhazia a sovereign country even if it is recognised by few other countries.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz side, however, has never accepted the paper as a basis for negotiations.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Eventually, Russia also withdrew its approval of the document.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2005 and 2008, the Georgian government offered Abkhazia a high degree of autonomy and possible federal structure within the borders and jurisdiction of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 18 October 2006, the People's Assembly of Abkhazia passed a resolution, calling upon Russia, international organisations and the rest of the international community to recognise Abkhaz independence on the basis that Abkhazia possesses all the properties of an independent state.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Georgia accuses the Abkhaz secessionists of having conducted a deliberate campaign of ethnic cleansing of up to 250,000 Georgians, a claim supported by the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE; Budapest, Lisbon and Istanbul declaration).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The UN Security Council has avoided the use of the term "ethnic cleansing" but has affirmed "the unacceptability of the demographic changes resulting from the conflict".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 15 May 2008, the United Nations General Assembly adopted a non-binding resolution recognising the right of all refugees (including victims of reported "ethnic cleansing") to return to Abkhazia and to retain or regain their property rights there.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 3 July 2008, the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly passed a resolution at its annual session in Astana, expressing concern over Russia's recent moves in breakaway Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 9 July 2012, the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly passed a resolution at its annual session in Monaco, underlining Georgia's territorial integrity and referring to breakaway Abkhazia and South Ossetia as "occupied territories".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In late October 2008, President Saakashvili signed into law legislation on the occupied territories passed by the Georgian Parliament.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The law covers the breakaway regions of Abkhazia and Tskhinvali (territories of the former South Ossetian Autonomous Oblast).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The law spells out restrictions on free movement and economic activity in the territories.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In particular, according to the law, foreign citizens should enter the two breakaway regions only through Georgia proper.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Entry into Abkhazia should be carried out from the Zugdidi Municipality, and into South Ossetia from the Gori Municipality.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The major road leading to South Ossetia from the rest of Georgia passes through the Gori District.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The legislation, however, also lists "special" cases in which entry into the breakaway regions will not be regarded as illegal.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] It also bans air, sea, and railway communications and international transit via the regions, mineral exploration, and money transfers.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The provision covering economic activities is retroactive, going back to 1990.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The law says that the Russian Federation – the state that has carried out military occupation – is fully responsible for the violation of human rights in Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Russian Federation, according to the document, is also responsible for compensation of material and moral damage inflicted on Georgian citizens, stateless persons, and foreign citizens, who are in Georgia and enter the occupied territories with appropriate permits.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The law also says that de facto state agencies and officials operating in the occupied territories are regarded by Georgia as illegal.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The law will remain in force until "the full restoration of Georgian jurisdiction" over the breakaway regions is realised.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to a 2006 report, Georgia considers all residents of Abkhazia its citizens, while they see themselves as Abkhaz citizens.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In the summer of 2011, the Parliament of Georgia adopted a package of legislative amendments providing for the issuance of neutral identification and travel documents to residents of Abkhazia and the former South Ossetian autonomous province of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The document allows travelling abroad as well as enjoying the social benefits existing in Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The new neutral identification and travel documents were called "neutral passports".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The status-neutral passports do not carry the state symbols of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia's foreign minister, Viacheslav Chirikba, criticised the status-neutral passports and called their introduction "unacceptable".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Some Abkhazian residents with Russian passports were being denied Schengen visas.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As of May 2013, neutral documents have been recognised by Japan, the Czech Republic, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia, the United States, Bulgaria, Poland, Israel, Estonia, and Romania.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] During the Georgian–Abkhaz conflict, the Russian authorities and military supplied logistical and military aid to the separatist side.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Today, Russia still maintains a strong political and military influence over separatist rule in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia has also issued passports to the citizens of Abkhazia since 2000 (as Abkhazian passports cannot be used for international travel) and subsequently paid them retirement pensions and other monetary benefits.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] More than 80% of the Abkhazian population had received Russian passports by 2006.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As Russian citizens living abroad, Abkhazians do not pay Russian taxes or serve in the Russian Army.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] About 53,000 Abkhazian passports have been issued as of May 2007.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Moscow, at certain times, hinted that it might recognise Abkhazia and South Ossetia when Western countries recognised the independence of Kosovo, suggesting that they had created a precedent.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Later in April 2008, Russia accused Georgia of trying to exploit NATO support in order to control Abkhazia by force and announced it would increase its military presence in the region, pledging to retaliate militarily against Georgia's efforts.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Georgian Prime Minister Lado Gurgenidze said Georgia will treat any additional troops in Abkhazia as "aggressors".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In response to the Russo-Georgian War, the Federal Assembly of Russia called an extraordinary session on 25 August 2008 to discuss the recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Following a unanimous resolution passed by both houses of the parliament calling on the Russian president to recognise the independence of the breakaway republics, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev officially recognised both on 26 August 2008.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russian recognition was condemned by NATO member states, OSCE, and European Council members due to "violation of territorial integrity and international law".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon stated that sovereign states have to decide for themselves whether they want to recognise the independence of disputed regions.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia has begun work on the establishment of a naval base in Ochamchire by dredging the coast to allow the passage of its larger naval vessels.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As a response to the Georgian sea blockade of Abkhazia, in which the Georgian coast guard had been detaining ships heading to and from Abkhazia, Russia warned Georgia against ship seizures and said that a unit of Russian guard boats would provide security for ships bound for Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The extent of Russian influence in Abkhazia has caused some locals to say that Abkhazia is under full Russian control, but they still prefer Russian influence over Georgian.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The UN's position has been that there will be no forcible change of international borders.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Any settlement must be freely negotiated and based on autonomy for Abkhazia, legitimised by referendum under international observation once the multi-ethnic population has returned.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The OSCE has increasingly engaged in dialogue with officials and civil society representatives in Abkhazia, especially from non-governmental organisations (NGOs) and the media, regarding human standards in the region, and is considering a presence in Gali.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The OSCE expressed concern and condemnation over the ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia during the 1994 Budapest Summit decision and later at the Lisbon Summit Declaration in 1996.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The US rejects the unilateral secession of Abkhazia and urges its integration into Georgia as an autonomous unit.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 1998, the US announced its readiness to allocate up to $15 million for the rehabilitation of infrastructure in the Gali region if substantial progress is made in the peace process.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] USAID has already funded some humanitarian initiatives for Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 5 October 2006, Javier Solana, the High Representative for the Common Foreign and Security Policy of the European Union, ruled out the possibility of replacing the Russian peacekeepers with the EU force.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] On 13 October 2006, the UN Security Council unanimously adopted a resolution, based on a Group of Friends of the Secretary-General draft, extending the UNOMIG mission until 15 April 2007.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Acknowledging that the "new and tense situation" resulted, at least in part, from the Georgian special forces' operation in the upper Kodori Valley, the resolution urged the country to ensure that no troops unauthorised by the Moscow ceasefire agreement were present in that area.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] It urged the leadership of the Abkhaz side to address seriously the need for a dignified, secure return of refugees and internally displaced persons and to reassure the local population in the Gali district that their residency rights and identity would be respected.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Calling on both parties to follow up on dialogue initiatives, it further urged them to comply fully with all previous agreements regarding non-violence and confidence-building, in particular those concerning the separation of forces.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Regarding the disputed role of the peacekeepers from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), the Council stressed the importance of close, effective cooperation between UNOMIG and that force and looked to all sides to continue to extend the necessary cooperation to them.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The HALO Trust, an international non-profit organisation that specialises in the removal of the debris of war, has been active in Abkhazia since 1999 and has completed the removal of landmines in Sukhumi and Gali districts.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] It declared Abkhazia "mine-free" in 2011.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] France-based international NGO Première-Urgence has been implementing a food security programme to support the vulnerable populations affected by the frozen conflict for almost 10 years.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia does not allow the European Union Monitoring Mission in Georgia (EUMM) to enter Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has been recognised as an independent state by only five states: Russia, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Nauru, and Syria.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Georgia and other countries consider Abkhazia as Georgia's sovereign territory.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia was the first country to officially recognise Abkhazia, which it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian War.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] After the Russian recognition, Nicaragua, Venezuela, Nauru, Vanuatu, and Tuvalu soon followed suit and recognised Abkhazia and South Ossetia as independent states.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] However, in 2013 and 2014, Vanuatu and Tuvalu scrapped their recognition.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia invested a significant amount of money in a diplomatic strategy to promote the recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia and display its soft power.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] However, Russia appeared to have stopped investing in the recognition project after 2014.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] One possible reason could be the worsening of Russia's financial situation following the start of the Russo-Ukrainian war in 2014 and the subsequent imposition of international sanctions on Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Consequently, Abkhazia launched its own campaign to strengthen its diplomatic relations with foreign countries and present itself as an independent actor.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As a part of these efforts, Abkhaz officials paid official visits to numerous countries, including China, Italy, Turkey, and Israel.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Additionally, they held high-level meetings with political representatives from South Africa, Jordan, and El Salvador, and sent diplomatic notes to different countries, including Egypt, France, Guatemala, and Sri Lanka.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] This campaign reached its peak in 2017, but subsequently decreased and largely halted with the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] It was largely unsuccessful and ended in failure as Syria remains the only country that has recognised Abkhazia and South Ossetia since 2009.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] One of the early proposals was voiced before the war, in March 1989, when the Abkhaz ethno-nationalist organisation Aidgylara issued the Lykhny Appeal, calling for Abkhazia to become part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] This is thought to be a starting point for the Abkhazia conflict between the separatists and local Georgian population in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] After the war, on 18 November 1993, a month after its ending and ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia, the leader of Abkhazia Vladislav Ardzinba proposed to hold a referendum to join the Russian Federation.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2001, a similar desire was voiced by Abkhazia's Prime Minister Anri Jergenia, who said that Abkhazia was preparing to join Russia and that it was going to hold a referendum on that issue.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In October 2022, in an interview to the Russian TV, President of Abkhazia Aslan Bzhania declared Abkhazia's readiness to host a Russian navy and join the Russia-Belarus Union State.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] However, the proposal has been criticised as impractical since Belarus does not recognise Abkhazia as a sovereign state and considers it to be part of Georgia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In August 2023, Deputy Chair of Russian Security Council Dmitry Medvedev also voiced support for these proposals, accusing Georgia of "escalating tensions" by its potential membership to the NATO, and saying that there were "good reasons" for Abkhazia and South Ossetia to join Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Medvedev also mocked Georgia's desire to restore its territorial integrity, saying that "Georgia can only be united as part of Russia".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Georgia criticised the proposals for Abkhazia's entry into the Russian Federation and Union State.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, Georgia's Foreign Ministry issued a statement, calling the Russia-Abkhazia treaty on integration a *de facto* annexation.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The economy of Abkhazia is integrated with Russia as outlined in a bilateral agreement published in November 2014.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The country uses the Russian ruble as its currency, and the two countries share a common economic and customs union.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has experienced a modest economic upswing since the 2008 South Ossetia war and Russia's subsequent recognition of Abkhazia's independence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] About half of Abkhazia's state budget is financed with aid money from Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Tourism is a key industry and, according to Abkhazia's authorities, almost a million tourists (mainly from Russia) came to Abkhazia in 2007.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia exports wine and fruits, especially tangerines and hazelnuts.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Electricity is largely supplied by the Inguri hydroelectric power station located on the Inguri River between Abkhazia and Georgia (proper) and operated jointly by both parties.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In the first half of 2012, the principal trading partners of Abkhazia were Russia (64%) and Turkey (18%).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia also called on other CIS members to undertake similar steps, but met with protests from Tbilisi and lack of support from the other CIS countries.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Despite the controversial status of the territory and its damaged infrastructure, tourism in Abkhazia grew following the Russian recognition of Abkhazian independence in 2008 due to the arrival of Russian tourists.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2009 the number of Russian tourists in Abkhazia increased by 20% and the total number of Russian tourists reached 1 million.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] After the tourist boom many Russian businesses began to invest money in Abkhazian tourist infrastructure.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] With the main highway of the country being rebuilt in 2014 many damaged hotels in Gagra are either being restored or demolished.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, 1.16 million Russian tourists visited Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to the last census in 2011 Abkhazia had 240,705 inhabitants.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Department of Statistics of Georgia estimated Abkhazia's population to be approximately 179,000 in 2003, and 178,000 in 2005 (the last year when such estimates were published in Georgia).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] *Encyclopædia Britannica* estimates the population in 2007 at 180,000 and the International Crisis Group estimated Abkhazia's total population in 2006 to be between 157,000 and 190,000 (or between 180,000 and 220,000 as estimated by UNDP in 1998).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The ethnic composition of Abkhazia has played a central role in the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The 1992–1993 war with Georgia resulted in the expulsion and flight of over half of the republic's population, which had numbered 525,061 in the 1989 census.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The population of Abkhazia remains ethnically very diverse, even after the 1992–1993 war.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] At present the population of Abkhazia is mainly made up of ethnic Abkhaz (50.7% according to the 2011 census), Russians, Armenians, Georgians (mostly Mingrelians, but also Svans), and Greeks.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Other ethnicities include Ukrainians, Belarusians, Ossetians, Tatars, Turks, Roma and Estonians.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Greeks constituted a significant minority in the area in the early 1920s (50,000), and remained a major ethnic group until 1945, when they were deported to Central Asia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Under the Soviet Union, the Russian, Armenian, and Georgian populations grew faster than the Abkhaz population, due to large-scale enforced migration, especially under the rule of Joseph Stalin and Lavrenty Beria.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] At the time of the 1989 census, Abkhazia's Georgian population numbered 239,872, forming around 45.7% of the population, and the Armenian population was 77,000.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Due to ethnic cleansing and displacement due to people fleeing the 1992–1993 war, the Georgian population, and to a lesser extent the Russian and Armenian populations, has greatly declined.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2003 Armenians formed the second-largest minority group in Abkhazia (closely matching the Georgians), numbering 44,869.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] By the time of the 2011 census, Georgians formed the second-largest minority group with a population of 46,455.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Despite the official numbers, unofficial sources estimate that the Abkhaz and Armenian communities are roughly equal in number.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In the wake of the Syrian civil war, Abkhazia granted refugee status to a few hundred Syrians with Abkhaz, Abazin and Circassian ancestry.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Facing a growing Armenian community, this move has been linked with the wish of the ruling Abkhaz —who have often been in the minority on their territory— to tilt the demographic balance in favour of the titular nation.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Thousands of Abkhaz, known as *muhajirun*, were exiled to the Ottoman Empire in the mid-19th century after resisting the Russian conquest of the Caucasus.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Today, Turkey is home to the world's largest Abkhaz diaspora community.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Size estimates vary – diaspora leaders say 1 million people; Abkhaz estimates range from 150,000 to 500,000.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The languages spoken in Abkhazia are Abkhaz, Russian, the Kartvelian languages Mingrelian and Svan, Armenian, and Greek.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Autonomous Republic passed a law in 2007 defining the Abkhaz language as the only state language of Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] As such, Abkhaz is the required language for legislative and executive council debates (with translation from and to Russian) and at least half of the text of all magazines and newspapers must be in Abkhaz.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Despite the official status of Abkhaz, the dominance of other languages within Abkhazia, especially Russian, is so great that experts called it an "endangered language" in 2004.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] During the Soviet era, language instruction would begin in schools in Abkhaz, only to switch to Russian for the majority of required schooling.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The government of the Republic is attempting to institute Abkhaz-only primary education but there has been limited success due to a lack of facilities and educational materials.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The primary schools in Kartvelian-speaking areas switched from Georgian to Russian in 2016.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] A majority of inhabitants of Abkhazia are Christian (Eastern Orthodox (see also: Abkhazian Orthodox Church) and Armenian Apostolic) while a significant minority are Sunni Muslim.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz Native Religion has undergone a strong revival in recent decades.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] There is a very small number of adherents of Judaism, Jehovah's Witnesses and new religious movements.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Jehovah's Witnesses organisation has officially been banned since 1995, though the decree is not currently enforced.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to the constitution of Abkhazia, the adherents of all religions have equal rights before the law.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to a survey held in 2003, 60% of respondents identified themselves as Christian, 16% as Muslim, 8% as atheist or irreligious, 8% as adhering to the traditional Abkhazian religion or as Pagan, 2% as follower of other religions and 6% as undecided.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] After the break-up of the Soviet Union, many Abkhazians kept their Soviet passports, even after a decade, and used them to eventually apply for Russian citizenship.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Before 2002, Russian law allowed residents of former Soviet Union to apply for citizenship if they had not become citizens of their newly independent states.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The new citizenship law of Russia adopted on 31 May 2002 introduced a simplified procedure of citizenship acquisition for former citizens of the Soviet Union regardless of their place of residence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In Abkhazia and South Ossetia, the application process was simplified even further, and people could apply even without leaving their homes.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russian non-governmental organisations with close ties to Russian officialdom simply took their papers to a nearby Russian city for processing.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazians began mass acquisition of Russian passports in 2002.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] It is reported that the public organisation the Congress of Russian Communities of Abkhazia started collecting Abkhazians' Soviet-era travel documents.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] It then sent them to a consular department specially set up by Russian Foreign Ministry officials in the city of Sochi.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] After they were checked, Abkhazian applicants were granted Russian citizenship.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] By 25 June 2002, an estimated 150,000 people in Abkhazia had acquired the new passports, joining 50,000 who already possessed Russian citizenship.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Sukhum authorities, although officially not involved in the registration for Russian nationality process, openly encouraged it.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Government officials said privately that President Putin's administration agreed with the passport acquisition during Abkhazia's prime minister Djergenia's visit to Moscow in May 2002.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] When the *"passportisation"* policy was launched in 2002, even Russia recognised Abkhazia as part of Georgia at that time.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Russia's extraterritorial naturalisation practice in South Ossetia and Abkhazia constituted an intervention contrary to international law and it violated Georgia's territorial sovereignty.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The passportisation caused outrage in Tbilisi, worsening its already shaky relations with Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Georgian Foreign Ministry issued a statement insisting that Abkhazians were citizens of Georgia and calling the passport allocation an "unprecedented illegal campaign".
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] President Eduard Shevardnadze said that he would be asking his Russian counterpart, Vladimir Putin, for an explanation.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The speaker of parliament Nino Burjanadze said that she would raise the matter at the forthcoming OSCE parliamentary assembly.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] 1 February 2011 was the last day in the post-Soviet era when a passport of USSR was valid for crossing the Russian-Abkhaz border.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to the staff of Abkhazia's passport and visa service, there were about two to three thousand mostly elderly people left with Soviet passports who had no chance of acquiring new documents.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] These people were not able to get Russian citizenship.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] But they can first get an internal Abkhaz passport and then a travelling passport to visit Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2005, citing the need to integrate ethnic Georgian residents of eastern districts of Abkhazia, the then leadership of Abkhazia showed signs of a softening stance towards granting of citizenship to the residents of Gali, Ochamchire and Tkvarcheli districts.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to the Abkhazian law on citizenship, ethnic Abkhazians, regardless of place of residence, can become Abkhaz citizens.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Those who are not ethnic Abkhazians are eligible for citizenship if they lived in Abkhazia for at least five years prior to the adoption of the act of independence in October 1999.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] This provision aimed at creating a legal hurdle in obtaining Abkhaz passports for those ethnic Georgians who fled Abkhazia as a result of 1992–1993 armed conflict and who then returned to the Gali district.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazian legislation forbids citizens of Abkhazia from holding dual citizenship with any other state apart from Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Ethnic Georgians who have returned to the Gali district and want to obtain Abkhaz passports, according to Abkhazian law, should undergo lengthy procedures which also include a requirement to submit documented proof that they renounced their Georgian citizenship.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] So in his official speeches, Bagapsh often added the Gali Georgians to population estimates of the Abkhaz, disregarding the fact that they still thought of themselves as ethnic Georgians rather than Abkhaz.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In early 2013 the process of passportisation of ethnic Georgians came under the scrutiny of Abkhaz opposition groups who turned this issue into one of the central topics of the breakaway region's internal politics, and issuing of passports was suspended in May.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Pressures have been placed upon teachers in areas of Abkhazia which retain large Georgian populations to abandon the use of the Georgian language in education and adopt Russian textbooks.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to the Abkhaz officials, more than 26,000 passports were distributed in Gali, Tkvarcheli and Ochamchire districts, including about 23,000 of which were given out since Russian recognition of Abkhazia's independence in August 2008.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] These political debates have caused concerns in the ethnic Georgian population of Abkhazia, who reside mainly in Gali district, that they would be stripped of Abkhazian citizenship and thus forced to leave Abkhazia again.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In October 2013 Alexander Ankvab signed a document ordering the firing of Stanislav Lakoba.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The document did not state any reason for the decision but Lakoba saw it as related to his political position on granting citizenship to Georgians living in Gali.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Lakoba claimed that, according to data from the Abkhaz Security Council, 129 local people in Gali fought against Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Local political parties and the coordination council of civil organisations expressed concern about Lakoba's dismissal.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] They claimed that, by dismissing him, the president "made an illegal process legal" – giving Abkhazian passports to Georgian citizens.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Until the 19th century, young people from Abkhazia usually received their education mainly at religious schools (Muslims at madrasas and Christians at seminaries), although a small number of children from wealthy families had opportunity to travel to foreign countries for education.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The first modern educational institutions (both schools and colleges) in Abkhazia were established in the late 19th-early 20th centuries and rapidly grew until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] By the middle of the 20th century, Sukhumi had become a home for large educational institutions (both higher education institutions and technical vocational education and training (TVET) colleges) and largest students' community in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] According to the official statistical data, Abkhazia has 12 TVET colleges (as of 2019, est.) providing education and vocational training to youth mostly in the capital city, though there are several colleges in all major district centres.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Independent international assessments suggest that these colleges train in about 20 different specialties attracting between 1000 and 1300 young people annually (aged between 16 and 29) (as of 2019, est.).
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The apsuara, the Abkhaz code of honour, is very stringent regarding hospitality.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] One of its principles is to respect guests even if they have committed crimes against the host.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The written Abkhaz literature appeared relatively recently, in the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] However, Abkhaz share the Nart sagas, a series of tales about mythical heroes, with other Caucasian peoples.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz alphabet was created in the 19th century.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The first newspaper in Abkhaz, called *Abkhazia* and edited by Dmitry Gulia, appeared in 1917.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Arguably the most famous Abkhaz writers are Fazil Iskander, who wrote mostly in Russian, and Bagrat Shinkuba, a poet and writer.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Football remains the most popular sport in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Other popular sports include basketball, boxing and wrestling.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] The National Basketball Team of Abkhazia played its first game with the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Basketball team on 27 May 2015, which Abkhaz team won by 76–59.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhaz basketball team "Apsny" also plays in the Russian Basketball League's Third-Tier in Krasnodar Krai.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has had its own amateur football league called the Abkhazian Premier League, but it has no international football union membership.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In total, there are nineteen Abkhazian Football Clubs across the two leagues.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] In 2016 it hosted and won the ConIFA World Football Cup.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Since the early 2000s, tennis has become increasingly popular among school age children in Abkhazia.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] Several tennis players from Sukhumi participated as the national competitions in Russia and played at major international competitions under the Russian flag.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazia-p02] For example, tennis player Alen Avidzba participated at the Davis Cup in 2016 and Amina Anshba won a silver medal at an international tournament in Turkey in 2017.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Lavrov in 1913 first proposed that Afro-Abkhazians originated in 5th-century BC Colchis.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Ancient sources including Herodotus and Jerome described Colchians as having dark skin, "wooly" hair, and an African origin.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Patrick English investigated this hypothesis further in 1959, citing ancient accounts of the region as well as anthropological and linguistic evidence.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Another origin hypothesis, which is more prevalent, is that Afro-Abkhazians were the first brought to Abkhazia through the Ottoman slave trade in the 17th or 18th centuries, having been purchased by Abkhazian royals.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] When the Ottomans withdrew from the region in the 19th century, those African slaves remaining in Abkhazia were freed.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] By the 19th century, Afro-Abkhazians had been mostly assimilated into the local Abkhaz population and were not viewed as a diaspora community.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] They were therefore not recognized as a distinct community by Soviet authorities.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Remaining Afro-Abkhazian villagers, who were impoverished and isolated, may have been subject to deportation to elsewhere in the Soviet Union.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Historically, the few scattered African communities in the Black Sea region were geographically isolated and unknown by the broader public.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Beginning in 1913 with an article by Russian researcher and naturalist V.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Vradii in the Tbilisi newspaper *Kavkaz*, the presence of Black communities in Abkhazia was repeatedly reported on in Russian newspapers.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Their origin and numbers were a subject of public debate in Russian media.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] In 1923, Soviet journalist Zinaida Richter visited a Black village near Sukhumi and reported on her expedition in the Moscow newspaper *Izvestia*.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Western periodicals also covered the subject in 1925 and 1931, when anthropologist B.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Adler publicized his research in *The New York Times*, in which he described small Black settlements whose inhabitants were of relatively unmixed ancestry.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Soviet anthropologists took interest in Afro-Abkhazians in the 1960s and produced several studies, although by this time the group was more dispersed and assimilated.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] In 1973 journalist Slava Tynes reported that there were still Afro-Abkhazian communities in villages like Adzyubzha, and noted their positive relationship with non-Black Abkhaz locals.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] During the Siege of Tkvarcheli operation in the 1992–1993 war, Georgian troops destroyed the three main villages that still had Afro-Abkhazian communities: Adzyubzha, Kindigh, and Tamsh.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] The descendants of Afro-Abkhazians mostly live in Abzhua Abkhazia (Ochamchira district), in the villages Adzyubzha, Chlou, Ilori, Kyndyg, Tamishi, Tkhyna and Reka.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Afro-Abkhazians have been recognized by other Abkhazians as being ethnically Abkhaz, as they have been culturally assimilated, and speak the Abkhaz language.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] Vradii exposited that the Afro-Abkhazians were mostly Muslim and spoke Abkhaz.
[src:african-diaspora/abkhazians-of-african-descent] In the 1970's, Fazil Iskander wrote about Afro-Abkhazians and their relationships with indigenous Abkhaz, which further popularized the subject.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal eventually rose to become a prominent member of the imperial court in the reign of Peter's daughter Elizabeth.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He had ten children, most of whom became members of the Russian nobility.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] One of his great-grandsons was the author and poet Alexander Pushkin.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The main reliable accounts of Gannibal's early life come from *The Moor of Peter the Great,* Pushkin's unfinished biography of his great-grandfather, published after Pushkin's death in 1837.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Scholars argue that Pushkin's account may be inaccurate due to the author’s desire to elevate the status of his ancestors and family.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] There are a number of contradictions between the biographies of Pushkin and the German novel *The Blackamoor of Peter the Great*, based on his great-grandfather.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Richard Pankhurst, the former professor at the Institute of Ethiopian Studies at the University of Addis Ababa in Ethiopia, believed the young Abram, Ibrahim or Abraham, as he named him, was born around 1698.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He was the son of a minor "prince" or chief.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] His father was relatively affluent, owning many livestock both inherited and taken in battle.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] However, after his father died in battle trying to defend his territory from the Ottoman Turks trying to conquer the Red Sea, Abram was captured and taken to Constantinople by ship.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] His sister, Lagan, is said to have drowned in the sea in a desperate attempt to save her brother.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Abram stayed in the Ottoman Empire for about a year in the service of Sultan Ahmed III's household.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] At the time, the Russian ambassador Sava Vladislavich-Raguzinsky, representing Peter the Great, was looking for "a few clever little African slaves" for the Tsar's palace in Moscow; a *Kammermohr* was a common feature of European courts of the time, as an exotic symbol of the court's prestige.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] On orders of Vladislavich's superiors (one of whom was Pyotr Andreyevich Tolstoy, great-grandfather of the celebrated writer Leo Tolstoy), Abram was selected for this purpose and soon ransomed from the Sultan's viziers with a bribe.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In 1704, the ambassador immediately dispatched him by land to Moscow in order to be presented to Tsar Peter the Great.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The Tsar is noted to have taken a liking to the boy's intelligence and potential for military service, and brought the child into his household.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Paraskeva Church in Vilnius, with Peter as his godfather.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The date of Gannibal’s baptism held personal significance; he used that date as his birthday because he did not know his actual date of birth.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Abram valued his relationship with his godfather, as well as that of Peter's daughter (Elizabeth), and was loyal to them as if they were family.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Starting at a young age, the boy Abram would travel alongside the emperor during his military campaigns, and at these military journeys he served as his godfather’s valet.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In 1717, Abram was sent to Metz, France, to receive an education in the arts, sciences and warfare from the highest institutes available.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] By then he was fluent in several languages and excelled in mathematics and geometry.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In 1718 Abram joined the French Royal Army with hopes of pleasing his godfather by expanding his learning in military engineering.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He enrolled in the royal artillery academy at La Fère in 1720.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] During Abram's studies, conflict broke out between France and Spain, and he fought in the War of the Quadruple Alliance, rising to the rank of captain.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] While fighting on the French side against Spain, Abram received a head injury and was captured by the Spanish army.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He was released in 1722 and continued his studies in Metz.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] It was during his time in France that Abram adopted the surname "Gannibal" in honor of the Carthaginian general Hannibal (*Gannibal* being the traditional transliteration of the name in Russian).
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In Paris he met and befriended such Enlightenment figures as Montesquieu and Voltaire (this claim by his biographer Hugh Barnes is disputed by reviewer Andrew Kahn).
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Voltaire called Gannibal the "dark star of the Enlightenment".
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal returned to Russia the following year and became first an engineer and then a mathematics tutor for one of the Tsar's private guard units.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal's education was completed by 1723, and he was due to return to Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] After the death of Peter in 1725, Prince Menshikov gained power in Russia due to his good standing with Peter.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] However, Menshikov was not fond of Gannibal and was suspicious of his foreign origins and superior education.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He first traveled to Kazan, then to Tobolsk and Irkutsk, and then to Selenginsk near the Mongolian border.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He was pardoned in 1730 due to his technical skills, and completed his service in Siberia in 1733.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] During this time he built a fortress and led several construction projects, where he became a master engineer.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Elizabeth of Russia became the new monarch in 1741.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal became a prominent member of her court, rose to the rank of major-general, and became superintendent of Reval (now Tallinn, Estonia), a position he held from 1742 to 1752.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Ganibal" is held at the Tallinn City Archives.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In 1742, the Empress Elizabeth gave him the Mikhailovskoye estate in Pskov Oblast with hundreds of serfs.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] After being made the chief military engineer of the Russian army in 1756, he received the rank of general-in-chief in 1759.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He eventually retired to the estate Empress Elizabeth gave him, in 1762 during the reign of Catherine the Great.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In an official document that Gannibal submitted in 1742 to Empress Elizabeth, while petitioning for the rank of nobility and a coat of arms, he asked for the right to use a family crest emblazoned with an elephant and the mysterious word "FVMMO", which may mean "homeland" in the Kotoko language.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In his book, *Gannibal: The Moor of Petersburg*, Hugh Barnes writes of meeting with the sultan of Logone-Birni, who gave him the same translation of the word.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] However, Frances Somers-Cocks, author of *The Moor of St Petersburg: In the Footsteps of a Black Russian*, met the same sultan and received a different translation for FVMMO.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] His first wife was Evdokia Dioper, a Greek woman.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Dioper despised her husband, whom she was forced to marry.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The marriage between Dioper and Gannibal was very volatile, and he suspected her of infidelity early in their marriage.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal’s suspicions were confirmed when Dioper gave birth to a white daughter.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] When Gannibal found out that she had been unfaithful to him, he had her arrested and thrown into prison, where she spent eleven years.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] His divorce from Dioper did not become final until 1753, upon which a fine and a penance were imposed on Gannibal, and Dioper was sent to a convent for the rest of her life.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal's second marriage was nevertheless deemed lawful after his divorce.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal’s second marriage to Christina was much happier, and he appreciated her fidelity and affection towards him.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] On her paternal side, Gannibal’s second wife was descended from noble families in Scandinavia and Germany: Siöberg (Sweden), Galtung (Norway), and Grabow (Denmark) / von Grabow (Brandenburg).
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Her paternal grandfather was Gustaf Siöberg, Rittmester til Estrup, who died in 1694, whose wife Clara Maria Lauritzdatter Galtung (ca.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] 1651–1698) was the daughter of Lauritz Lauritzson Galtung (ca.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Abram Gannibal and Christine Regina Siöberg had ten children.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Their oldest son, Ivan, became an accomplished naval officer who helped found the city of Kherson in southern Ukraine in 1779 and attained the rank of general-in-chief, the second-highest military rank in imperial Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Another son, Osip, had a daughter, Nadezhda, who became the mother of the great writer Alexander Pushkin.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] More than one British aristocratic family descends from Pushkin, notably the Grosvenors (Duke of Westminster via Anastasia de Torby) and the Mountbattens (Marquess of Milford Haven, via Anastasia's sister Nadejda de Torby).
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gannibal's actual place of birth continues to be uncertain, and is subject to speculation by modern historians.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Until recent scholarly field work, it was generally assumed that he originated in Ethiopia.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Chiefly Russian scholars for many years believed that he was from the vicinity of Mereb Melash, a province in present-day Eritrea.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In a letter he wrote to Empress Elizabeth, Peter the Great's daughter, Gannibal stated that he was from the town of "Logon" or "Lagone".
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Anthropologist Dmitry Anuchin wrote an essay about Alexander Pushkin in which he theorized that "Lagone" referred to Logo-chewa in Eritrea.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In 1999, the Russian Institute in Addis Ababa, the capital of Ethiopia, also campaigned for a commemorative stamp to honor Pushkin's bicentennial.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The governments of Ethiopia and Eritrea each claim that Gannibal was born in their respective territories.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Under this belief, the Ethiopian government named a street in Addis Ababa after Alexander Pushkin, Gannibal's great-grandson.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] It also placed a bust of him near the African Union headquarters in 2002, and arranged for a statue of Pushkin to be transferred from Moscow to Addis Ababa in 2014.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] However, the notion that Gannibal may have been born in Ethiopia holds little currency with the general Ethiopian population.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The Eritrean government asserts that Gannibal was instead born in Loggo Sarda, an area in modern Eritrea.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] It also erected its own statue of Pushkin and named a street after him in 2009.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Vladimir Nabokov cast doubt on Gannibal's ancestry, based on research findings during his work translating Pushkin's novel *Eugene Onegin*.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The Beninese historian Dieudonné Gnammankou, an expert on Russia, studied Russian, French and African sources and argued that Gannibal was indeed from Logone-Birni and was most likely the son of a chief in the ancient sultanate.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In 1995, Gnammankou asserted that the "Logon" Gannibal wrote about was actually Logone, capital of the old Kotoko kingdom of Logone-Birni, now located in northern Cameroon.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He believed that the pattern of slave trade around Lake Chad made that region a more plausible likelihood for Gannibal's birthplace than Gondar, Ethiopia.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gnammankou's biography of Gannibal was translated into Russian, and was voted the best book on Pushkin at the 1999 Moscow Book Fair.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Gnammankou's findings were in turn buttressed by the field work of Hugh Barnes.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] After consulting with the Sultan of Logone-Birni, Barnes found that an inscription on Gannibal's crest, which was hitherto undecipherable, corresponded with the term for "homeland" in the local Kotoko language of central Africa.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] She also suggested that FVMMO stands for the Latin expression *Fortuna Vitam Meam Mutavit Omnino*, which means "Fortune has changed my life entirely".
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In November 2010, representatives from Russia and Estonia, the ambassador of Cameroon, and the sultan of Logone-Birni went to La Fère, France to unveil a commemorative plaque honoring Abram Petrovich Gannibal as a graduate of La Fère's royal artillery academy.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The academy, which closed in the 1990s, had been started by King Louis XV shortly before Gannibal's enrollment there in 1720.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The plaque declares that he was a graduate of the royal artillery academy of La Fère, and later became chief military engineer and general-in-chief of the Imperial Russian Army.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] It also notes that Gannibal is the great-grandfather of Alexander Pushkin, Russia's greatest poet.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Dieudonné Gnammankou, whose research into Gannibal's background was largely responsible for the ceremony at La Fère taking place, also served as the main speaker at a symposium following the event.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Alexander Pushkin used his great-grandfather Abram Gannibal as the model for Ibrahim, the lead character in his unfinished novel *The Moor of Peter the Great*.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] After leaving school in 1817, Pushkin met Abram's last surviving son, Peter.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] He met Peter again in 1825, after writing in his diary about wanting to "get from him some memoirs about my great-grandfather." He seemed to use his own experiences, along with Gannibal's to create the plot for *The Moor of Peter the Great*.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] A stage version of the work was written by Carlyle Brown and premiered at the Alabama Shakespeare Festival's 13th Southern Writers' Project in March 2001.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Abram Gannibal is a protagonist of the Soviet comedy movie *How Czar Peter the Great Married Off His Moor*, although the film's plot has almost nothing to do with Gannibal's real biography.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The film is partly based on Pushkin's *Moor of Peter the Great*.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] There are several portraits thought to depict Gannibal, which include a painting of the Battle of Lesnaya by Pierre-Denis Martin the Younger.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] The young boy present in Martin’s painting is argued to be Gannibal, because of the young boy’s role as valet to Peter during military campaigns and Gannibal’s possible connection to the artist while in France.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] A portrait by Adriaan Schoonebeeck is also believed to portray Gannibal during his time with Peter the Great.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In Schoonebeeck’s portrait of Peter the Great, the young servant boy directly behind Peter is thought to be Gannibal.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] Although there are a variety of portraits that claim to contain Gannibal, there is little evidence to suggest the claims are accurate.
[src:african-diaspora/abram-petrovich-gannibal] In the Lesnaya painting, the young boy is dressed in traditional slave attire, which Gannibal did not wear due to his status under Peter the Great.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The **African diaspora** is the worldwide collection of communities that descended from people from Africa.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The term most commonly refers to emigrants of people of African heritage but could also refer to descendants of enslaved Africans.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Scholars typically identify "four circulatory phases" of this migration out of Africa.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The phrase *African diaspora* gradually entered common usage at the turn of the 21st century.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The term *diaspora* originates from the Greek word διασπορά (*diaspora*, "scattering") which gained popularity in English in reference to the Jewish diaspora before being more broadly applied to other populations.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Less commonly, the term has been used in scholarship to refer to more recent emigration from Africa.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Its constitutive act declares that it shall "invite and encourage the full participation of the African diaspora as an important part of our continent, in the building of the African Union".
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In the late 20th century, Africans began to emigrate to Europe and the Americas in increasing numbers, constituting new African diaspora communities.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In the Americas, the confluence of multiple ethnic groups from around the world contributed to multi-ethnic societies.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In Central and South America, most people are descended from European, Native American, and African ancestry.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In 1888, in Brazil nearly half the population were people of African descent, the variation of physical characteristics extends across a broad range.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The diaspora that resulted from the Atlantic slave trade, specifically, may also be referred to as the black diaspora.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Many scholars have challenged conventional views of the African diaspora as a mere dispersion of African people.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] For them, it is a movement of liberation that opposes the implications of racialization.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Their position assumes that Africans and their descendants abroad struggle to reclaim power over their lives through voluntary migration, cultural production and political conceptions and practices.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] It also implies the presence of cultures of resistance with similar objectives throughout the global diaspora.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Dubois and more recently Robin Kelley, for example, have argued that black politics of survival reveal more about the meaning of the African diaspora than labels of ethnicity and race, and degrees of skin hue.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] From this view, the daily struggle against what they call the "world-historical processes" of racial colonization, capitalism, and Western domination defines blacks' links to Africa.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In the last decades, studies on the African diaspora have shown an interest in the roles that Africans played in bringing about modernity.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] This trend also opposes the traditional eurocentric perspective that has dominated history books showing Africans and its diasporans as primitive victims of slavery, and without historical agency.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] According to historian Patrick Manning, blacks toiled at the center of forces that created the modern world.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Paul Gilroy describes the suppression of blackness due to imagined and created ideals of nations as "cultural insiderism".
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Cultural insiderism is used by nations to separate deserving and undeserving groups and requires a "sense of ethnic difference" as mentioned in his book *The Black Atlantic*.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Recognizing their contributions offers a comprehensive appreciation of global history.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The African diaspora has shaped global culture, specifically in music and literature.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Musical forms rooting from Black communities in the Americas and the Caribbean such as jazz, reggae, samba, and hiphop.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Hip hop is one of the best examples and it started in the Bronx, created by African American and Afro-Caribbean youth and has grown into one of the most popular music genres around the world.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Writers from the African diaspora have also made contributions by sharing stories about identity, family, migration, and the sense of belonging.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Through literature, people are able to understand what diaspora life is really like and it gives a voice to experiences from the past.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The influence of the African diaspora can be seen everywhere, from songs people listen to, and to the books they read.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] All of this helps show that the culture from the African diaspora still has an impact on the modern world.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Cultural and political theorist Richard Iton suggested that diaspora be understood as a "culture of dislocation".
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] A diaspora is defined as a dispersion of a people, language, or culture that was formerly concentrated in one place, to scatter, to displace, to live in separated communities.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The African diaspora is defined as including all African descendants to various parts of the world, particularly of slave trades such as the Trans-Atlantic slave trade, which includes mixed-race people with African ancestry and therefore does not rely on only self-identifying as black.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In multiple Latin American countries, many mixed-race people have African ancestry and therefore are considered afrodescendants.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In all these cases, diasporic labels are used to recognise lineage and historical connection rather than present-day identity.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Afrodescendant inclusion functions similarly: it marks ancestry, not how someone chooses to identify in daily life, in which mixed-race people, such as pardo Brazilians or mixed Dominicans, are of African ancestry, as well as others.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The first Africans in the Americas arrived in the region during the initial period of European colonization.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In 1492, Afro-Spanish sailor Pedro Alonso Niño served as a pilot on the voyages of Christopher Columbus; though he returned to the Americas in 1499, Niño did not settle in the region.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] By the early 16th century, more Africans began to arrive in Spanish colonies in the Americas, sometimes as free people of color, but the majority were enslaved.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Demand of African labor increased as the indigenous population of the Americas experienced a massive population decline due to the introduction of Eurasian infectious diseases (such as smallpox) to which they had no natural immunity.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Spanish Crown granted *asientos* (monopoly contracts) to merchants granting them the right to supply enslaved Africans in to Spanish colonies in the Americas, regulating the trade.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] As other European nations began establishing colonies in the Americas, these new colonies began importing enslaved Africans as well.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] During the 17th and 18th centuries, most European colonies in the Caribbean operated on plantation economies fueled by slave labor, and the resulting importation of enslaved Africans meant that Afro-Caribbeans soon far outnumbered their European enslavers in terms of population.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Roughly eleven to twelve million enslaved Africans were transported to the Americas as part of the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Beginning in 1791, the Haitian Revolution, a slave rebellion by self-emancipated slaves in the French colony of Saint-Domingue eventually led to the creation of the Republic of Haiti.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The new state, led by Jean Jacques Dessalines was the first nation in the Americas to be established from a successful slave revolt and represented a challenge to the existing slave systems in the region.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Continuous waves of slave rebellions, such as the Baptist War led by Samuel Sharpe in British Jamaica, created the conditions for the incremental abolition of slavery in the region, with Great Britain abolishing it in the 1830s.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Spanish colony of Cuba was the last Caribbean island to emancipate its slaves.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] During the 20th century, Afro-Caribbean people began to assert their cultural, economic and political rights on the world stage.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Jamaican Marcus Garvey formed the UNIA movement in the United States, continuing with Aimé Césaire's négritude movement, which was intended to create a pan-African movement across national lines.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] From the 1960s, the decolonization of the Americas led to various Caribbean countries gaining their independence from European colonial rule.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] They were pre-eminent in creating new cultural forms such as calypso, reggae music, and Rastafari within the Caribbean.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Beyond the region, a new Afro-Caribbean diaspora, including such figures as Stokely Carmichael and DJ Kool Herc in the United States, was influential in the creation of the black power and hip hop movements.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Influential political theorists such as Walter Rodney, Frantz Fanon and Stuart Hall contributed to anti-colonial theory and movements in Africa, as well as cultural developments in Europe.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Several migration waves to the Americas, as well as relocations within the Americas, have brought people of African descent to North America.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] According to the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture, the first African populations came to North America in the 16th century via Mexico and the Caribbean to the Spanish colonies of Florida, Texas and other parts of the South.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Out of the 12 million people from Africa who were shipped to the Americas during the transatlantic slave trade, 645,000 were shipped to the British colonies on the North American mainland and the United States.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In 2000, African Americans comprised 12.1 percent of the total population in the United States, constituting the largest racial minority group.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The African-American population is concentrated in the southern states and urban areas.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In the 1860s, people from sub-Saharan Africa, mainly from West Africa and the Cape Verde Islands, started to arrive in a voluntary immigration wave to seek employment as whalers in Massachusetts.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] This migration continued until restrictive laws were enacted in 1921 that in effect closed the door on non-Europeans.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] By that time, men of African ancestry were already a majority in New England's whaling industry, with African Americans working as sailors, blacksmiths, shipbuilders, officers, and owners.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The internationalism of whaling crews, including the character Daggoo, an African harpooneer, is recorded in the 1851 novel *Moby-Dick*.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] They eventually took their trade to California.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Today 1.7 million people in the United States are descended from voluntary immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa, most of whom arrived in the late twentieth century.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] African immigrants represent 6 percent of all immigrants to the United States and almost 5 percent of the African-American community nationwide.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] About 57 percent immigrated between 1990 and 2000.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Immigrants born in Africa constitute 1.6 percent of the black population.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] People of the African immigrant diaspora are the most educated population group in the United States—50 percent have bachelor's or advanced degrees, compared to 23 percent of native-born Americans.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The largest African immigrant communities in the United States are in New York, followed by California, Texas, and Maryland.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Due to the legacy of slavery in the colonial history of the United States, the average African American has a significant European component to his DNA.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] According to a study conducted in 2011, the African American DNA consists on average of 73.2% West African, 24% European and 0.8% Native American DNA.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The European ancestry of African Americans is largely patrilineal with an estimated 19% of African American ancestors being European males, and 5% being European females.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The interracial mixing occurred before the Civil War and largely in the American South, beginning during the colonial era.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The states with the highest percentages of people of African descent are Mississippi (36%), and Louisiana (33%).
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] While not a state, the population of the District of Columbia is more than 50% black.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Recent African immigrants represent a minority of black people nationwide.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Bureau of the Census categorizes the population by race based on self-identification.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The census surveys have no provision for a "multiracial" or "biracial" self-identity, but since 2000, respondents may check off more than one box and claim multiple ethnicity that way.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Much of the earliest black presence in Canada came from the newly independent United States after the American Revolution.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The British resettled African Americans (known as Black Loyalists) primarily in Nova Scotia.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] These were primarily former slaves who had escaped to British lines for promised freedom during the Revolution.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Later during the antebellum years, other individual African Americans escaped to Canada, mostly to locations in Southwestern Ontario, via the Underground Railroad, a system supported by both blacks and whites to assist fugitive slaves.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] After achieving independence, northern states in the U.S. had begun to abolish slavery as early as 1793, but slavery was not abolished in the South until 1865, following the American Civil War.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Black immigration to Canada in the twentieth century consisted mostly of Caribbean descent.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] As a result of the prominence of Caribbean immigration, the term "African Canadian", while sometimes used to refer to the minority of Canadian blacks who have direct African or African-American heritage, is *not* normally used to denote black Canadians.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] At an intermediate level, in South America and in the former plantations in and around the Indian Ocean, descendants of enslaved people are a bit harder to define because many people are mixed in demographic proportion to the original slave population.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In places that imported relatively few slaves (like Chile), few if any are considered "black" today.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In places that imported many enslaved people (like Brazil or Dominican Republic), the number is larger, though most identify themselves as being of mixed, rather than strictly African, ancestry.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In places like Brazil and the Dominican Republic, blackness is performed in more taboo ways than it is in, say, the United States.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The idea behind Trey Ellis Cultural Mulatto comes into play as there are blurred lines between what is considered as black.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In Colombia, the African slaves were first brought to work in the gold mines of the Department of Antioquia.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] After this was no longer a profitable business, these slaves slowly moved to the Pacific coast, where they have remained unmixed with the white or Indian population until today.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The whole Department of Chocó remains a black area.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Mixture with white population happened mainly in the Caribbean coast, which is a mestizo area until today.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] There was also a greater mixture in the south-western departments of Cauca and Valle del Cauca.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In these mestizo areas the African culture has had a great influence.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The people have retained their language, beliefs and the associated rituals.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Some European countries make it illegal to collect demographic census information based on ethnicity or ancestry (e.g.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] France), but some others do query along racial lines (e.g. the UK).
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Of 42 countries surveyed by a European Commission against Racism and Intolerance study in 2007, it was found that 29 collected official statistics on country of birth, 37 on citizenship, 24 on religion, 26 on language, 6 on country of birth of parents, and 22 on nationality or ethnicity.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Estimates of 8 to 10 million of African descent, although one quarter of the Afro-French population live in overseas territories.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] This number is difficult to estimate because the French census does not use race as a category for ideological reasons.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] As of 2020, there were approximately 1,000,000 Afro-Germans.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] This number is difficult to estimate because the German census does not use race as a category.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Some black people of unknown origin (Though perceived as Ethiopians) once inhabited southern Abkhazia; today, they have been assimilated into the Abkhaz population.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] African emigrants to Italy include Italian citizens and residents originally from Africa; immigrants from Africa officially residing in Italy in 2015 numbered over 1 million residents.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] There are an estimated 500,000 African or mixed African people in the Netherlands and the Dutch Antilles.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] They mainly live in the islands of Aruba, Bonaire, Curaçao and Saint Martin, the latter of which is also partly French-controlled.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Many Afro-Dutch people reside in the Netherlands.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] As of 2023, is up to 700,000 people of recent Native African immigrant background living in Portugal.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] They mainly live in the regions of Lisbon metropolitan area.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] They mainly live in the regions of Andalusia, Catalonia, Madrid and the Canaries.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] There are about 2,500,000 (4.2%) people identifying as Black British (not including British Mixed), among which are Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] They live mostly in urban areas in England.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The first Black people in Russia were the result of the slave trade of the Ottoman Empire and their descendants still live on the coasts of the Black Sea.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Czar Peter the Great was advised by his friend Lefort to bring in Africans to Russia for hard labor.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Alexander Pushkin's great-grandfather was the African princeling Abram Petrovich Gannibal, who became Peter's protégé, was educated as a military engineer in France, and eventually became general-en-chef, responsible for the building of sea forts and canals in Russia.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] During the 1930s fifteen Black American families moved to the Soviet Union as agricultural experts.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] As African states became independent in the 1960s, the Soviet Union offered their citizens the chance to study in Russia; over 40 years, 400,000 African students came, and some settled there.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Afro-Turks are people of Zanj (Bantu) descent living in Turkey.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Like the Afro-Abkhazians, they trace their origins to the Ottoman slave trade.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Beginning several centuries ago, a number of Africans came to the Ottoman Empire, usually via Zanzibar as Zanj and from places such as present-day Niger, Saudi Arabia, Libya, Kenya and Sudan; they settled by the Dalaman, Menderes and Gediz valleys, Manavgat, and Çukurova.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In the 19th century, contemporary records mention African quarters of İzmir, including Sabırtaşı, Dolapkuyu, Tamaşalık, İkiçeşmelik, and Ballıkuyu.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Africans in Turkey are around 100.000 people.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] There are a number of communities in South Asia that are descended from African slaves, traders or soldiers.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] These communities are the Siddi, Sheedi, Makrani and Sri Lanka Kaffirs.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In some cases, they became very prominent, such as Jamal-ud-Din Yaqut, Hoshu Sheedi, Malik Ambar, or the rulers of Janjira State.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Mauritian creole people are the descendants of African slaves similar to those in the Americas.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The **Siddi** (pronounced [sɪd̪d̪i]), also known as the **Sheedi**, **Sidi**, **Siddhi**, or **Habshi**, are an ethnic group inhabiting India and Pakistan.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Members are mostly descended from the Bantu peoples of Southeast Africa, along with Habesha immigrants.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Some were merchants, sailors, indentured servants, slaves and mercenaries.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Siddi population is currently estimated at 850,000 individuals, with Karnataka, Gujarat and Telangana states in India and Makran and Karachi in Pakistan as the main population centres.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Siddis are primarily Muslims, although some are Hindus and others belong to the Catholic Church.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Although often economically and socially marginalised as a community today, Siddis once ruled Bengal as the Habshi dynasty of the Bengal Sultanate, while the famous Siddi, Malik Ambar, effectively controlled the Ahmadnagar Sultanate.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] He played a major role, politically and militarily, in Indian history by slowing down the penetration of the Delhi-based Mughals into the Deccan Plateau of South central India.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Some Pan-Africanists also consider other peoples as diasporic African peoples.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] These groups include, among others, Negritos, such as in the case of the peoples of the Malay Peninsula (Orang Asli); New Guinea (Papuans); Andamanese; certain peoples of the Indian subcontinent, and the aboriginal peoples of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Most of these claims are rejected by mainstream ethnologists as pseudoscience and pseudo-anthropology, as part of ideologically motivated Afrocentrist irredentism, touted primarily among some extremist elements in the United States who do not reflect on the mainstream African-American community.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Mainstream anthropologists determine that the Andamanese and others are part of a network of autochthonous ethnic groups present in South Asia that trace their genetic ancestry to a migratory sequence that culminated in the Australian Aboriginals rather than from Africa directly.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Genetic testing has shown the Andamani to belong to the Y-Chromosome Haplogroup D-M174, which is in common with Australian Aboriginals and the Ainu people of Japan rather than the actual African diaspora.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Kingdom of Aksum was an ancient empire in what is now northern Ethiopia.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] There were four invasions and subsequent settlements of Aksumites in Himyar, located across the Red Sea in modern-day Yemen.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] These invasions and settlements led to one of the first large-scale African diasporas in the ancient world.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In 517 AD, the Himyarite king Ma'adikarib was overthrown by Dhu Nuwas, a Jewish leader who began persecuting Christians and confiscating trade goods between Aksum and the Byzantine Empire, both of which were Christian nations.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] According to the *Book of the Himyarites*, a man identified as Bishop Thomas journeyed to Aksum to report on the persecution of Christians in Himyar to the Aksumite Kingdom.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] As a result, the Aksumite king Ahayawa invaded Himyar.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Dhu Nuwas fled this first invasion, and at least 580 Aksumite soldiers remained in Himyar.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Himyarites who opposed Aksumite settlement united under Dhu Nuwas, and the formerly expelled king traveled back to kill the Aksumite soldiers and continue the oppression of Christians, forcing some settlers back into Aksum.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] In response to Dhu Nuwas's Christian persecution, the new Aksumite king Kaleb first sent a group of Himyarite refugees in his Aksumite kingdom back into Himyar to stir up underground resistance against Dhu Nuwas.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] These discontented Himyarites then united under nobleman Sumyafa Ashwa.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Kaleb successfully invaded Himyar with an Aksumite army in 525 and installed Sumyafa Ashwa to rule.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] More Aksumite soldiers remained in Himyar to claim land.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Byzantine ruler Justinian learned of this development and sent an ambassador, Julianus, to ally Aksum and Himyar with the Byzantine Empire against Persia.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Justinian had two wishes for this proposed alliance: first, for Aksum to purchase and distribute Indian silk to the Byzantine Empire to undermine Persia economically, and second, for Aksum-ruled Himyar to invade Persia, led by the general Caisus.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Both of these plans failed, as Persia's proximity to India made the interruption of their silk trade impossible, and neither Himyar nor Aksum saw value in attacking an adversary that was both stronger and far too distant.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Caisus was also responsible for killing a relative of Sumyafa Ashwa's, making Aksumites unwilling to go into battle under him.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] A third invasion was prompted by a rebellion of Aksumite soldiers between 532 and 535, led by the former slave and Aksumite commander Abreha, against Sumyafa Ashwa.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Kaleb sent 3,000 soldiers to quell this rebellion, led by one of his relatives, but these soldiers joined Abreha's rebellion upon arrival and killed Kaleb's relative.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Kaleb sent reinforcements in another attempt to end the rebellion, but his soldiers were defeated and forced to turn around.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Following Kaleb's death, Abreha paid tribute to Aksum to reinforce Himyar's independence.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The new Himyarite nation consisted of several thousand Aksumite emigrants, serving as one of the earliest examples of a large-scale movement of tropical Africans outside of the continent.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] Although fragmented and separated by land and water, the African Diaspora maintains connection through the use of music.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] This link between the various sects of the African Diaspora is termed by Paul Gilroy as The Black Atlantic.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The Black Atlantic is possible because black people have a shared history rooted in oppression that is displayed in Black genres such as rap and reggae.
[src:african-diaspora/african-diaspora] The linkages within the black diaspora formulated through music allows consumers of music and artists to pull from different cultures to combine and create a conglomerate of experiences that reaches across the world.
